71// Define attributes of all API symbols declarations (e.g. for DLL under Windows)
72// IMGUI_API is used for core imgui functions, IMGUI_IMPL_API is used for the default backends files (imgui_impl_xxx.h)
73// Using dear imgui via a shared library is not recommended: we don't guarantee backward nor forward ABI compatibility + this is a call-heavy library and function call overhead adds up.
74#ifndef IMGUI_API
75#define IMGUI_API
76#endif
77#ifndef IMGUI_IMPL_API
78#define IMGUI_IMPL_API IMGUI_API
79#endif

81// Helper Macros
82#ifndef IM_ASSERT
83#include <assert.h>
84#define IM_ASSERT(_EXPR) assert(_EXPR) // You can override the default assert handler by editing imconfig.h
85#endif
86#define IM_ARRAYSIZE(_ARR) ((int)(sizeof(_ARR) / sizeof(*(_ARR)))) // Size of a static C-style array. Don't use on pointers!
87#define IM_UNUSED(_VAR) ((void)(_VAR)) // Used to silence "unused variable warnings". Often useful as asserts may be stripped out from final builds.
88#define IMGUI_CHECKVERSION() ImGui::DebugCheckVersionAndDataLayout(IMGUI_VERSION, sizeof(ImGuiIO), sizeof(ImGuiStyle), sizeof(ImVec2), sizeof(ImVec4), sizeof(ImDrawVert), sizeof(ImDrawIdx))

90// Helper Macros - IM_FMTARGS, IM_FMTLIST: Apply printf-style warnings to our formatting functions.
91#if !defined(IMGUI_USE_STB_SPRINTF) && defined(__MINGW32__) && !defined(__clang__)
92#define IM_FMTARGS(FMT) __attribute__((format(gnu_printf, FMT, FMT+1)))
93#define IM_FMTLIST(FMT) __attribute__((format(gnu_printf, FMT, 0)))
94#elif !defined(IMGUI_USE_STB_SPRINTF) && (defined(__clang__) || defined(__GNUC__))
95#define IM_FMTARGS(FMT) __attribute__((format(printf, FMT, FMT+1)))
96#define IM_FMTLIST(FMT) __attribute__((format(printf, FMT, 0)))
97#else
98#define IM_FMTARGS(FMT)
99#define IM_FMTLIST(FMT)
100#endif

102// Disable some of MSVC most aggressive Debug runtime checks in function header/footer (used in some simple/low-level functions)
103#if defined(_MSC_VER) && !defined(__clang__) && !defined(__INTEL_COMPILER) && !defined(IMGUI_DEBUG_PARANOID)
104#define IM_MSVC_RUNTIME_CHECKS_OFF __pragma(runtime_checks("",off)) __pragma(check_stack(off)) __pragma(strict_gs_check(push,off))
105#define IM_MSVC_RUNTIME_CHECKS_RESTORE __pragma(runtime_checks("",restore)) __pragma(check_stack()) __pragma(strict_gs_check(pop))
106#else
107#define IM_MSVC_RUNTIME_CHECKS_OFF
108#define IM_MSVC_RUNTIME_CHECKS_RESTORE
109#endif

111// Warnings
112#ifdef _MSC_VER
113#pragma warning (push)
114#pragma warning (disable: 26495) // [Static Analyzer] Variable 'XXX' is uninitialized. Always initialize a member variable (type.6).
115#endif
116#if defined(__clang__)
117#pragma clang diagnostic push
118#if __has_warning("-Wunknown-warning-option")
119#pragma clang diagnostic ignored "-Wunknown-warning-option" // warning: unknown warning group 'xxx'
120#endif
121#pragma clang diagnostic ignored "-Wunknown-pragmas" // warning: unknown warning group 'xxx'
122#pragma clang diagnostic ignored "-Wold-style-cast"
123#pragma clang diagnostic ignored "-Wzero-as-null-pointer-constant"
124#pragma clang diagnostic ignored "-Wreserved-identifier" // warning: identifier '_Xxx' is reserved because it starts with '_' followed by a capital letter
125#elif defined(__GNUC__)
126#pragma GCC diagnostic push
127#pragma GCC diagnostic ignored "-Wpragmas" // warning: unknown option after '#pragma GCC diagnostic' kind
128#pragma GCC diagnostic ignored "-Wclass-memaccess" // [__GNUC__ >= 8] warning: 'memset/memcpy' clearing/writing an object of type 'xxxx' with no trivial copy-assignment; use assignment or value-initialization instead

135// Forward declarations
136struct ImDrawChannel; // Temporary storage to output draw commands out of order, used by ImDrawListSplitter and ImDrawList::ChannelsSplit()
137struct ImDrawCmd; // A single draw command within a parent ImDrawList (generally maps to 1 GPU draw call, unless it is a callback)
138struct ImDrawData; // All draw command lists required to render the frame + pos/size coordinates to use for the projection matrix.
139struct ImDrawList; // A single draw command list (generally one per window, conceptually you may see this as a dynamic "mesh" builder)
140struct ImDrawListSharedData; // Data shared among multiple draw lists (typically owned by parent ImGui context, but you may create one yourself)
141struct ImDrawListSplitter; // Helper to split a draw list into different layers which can be drawn into out of order, then flattened back.
142struct ImDrawVert; // A single vertex (pos + uv + col = 20 bytes by default. Override layout with IMGUI_OVERRIDE_DRAWVERT_STRUCT_LAYOUT)
143struct ImFont; // Runtime data for a single font within a parent ImFontAtlas
144struct ImFontAtlas; // Runtime data for multiple fonts, bake multiple fonts into a single texture, TTF/OTF font loader
145struct ImFontBuilderIO; // Opaque interface to a font builder (stb_truetype or FreeType).
146struct ImFontConfig; // Configuration data when adding a font or merging fonts
147struct ImFontGlyph; // A single font glyph (code point + coordinates within in ImFontAtlas + offset)
148struct ImFontGlyphRangesBuilder; // Helper to build glyph ranges from text/string data
149struct ImColor; // Helper functions to create a color that can be converted to either u32 or float4 (*OBSOLETE* please avoid using)
150struct ImGuiContext; // Dear ImGui context (opaque structure, unless including imgui_internal.h)
151struct ImGuiIO; // Main configuration and I/O between your application and ImGui
152struct ImGuiInputTextCallbackData; // Shared state of InputText() when using custom ImGuiInputTextCallback (rare/advanced use)
153struct ImGuiKeyData; // Storage for ImGuiIO and IsKeyDown(), IsKeyPressed() etc functions.
154struct ImGuiListClipper; // Helper to manually clip large list of items
155struct ImGuiOnceUponAFrame; // Helper for running a block of code not more than once a frame
156struct ImGuiPayload; // User data payload for drag and drop operations
157struct ImGuiPlatformImeData; // Platform IME data for io.SetPlatformImeDataFn() function.
158struct ImGuiSizeCallbackData; // Callback data when using SetNextWindowSizeConstraints() (rare/advanced use)
159struct ImGuiStorage; // Helper for key->value storage
160struct ImGuiStyle; // Runtime data for styling/colors
161struct ImGuiTableSortSpecs; // Sorting specifications for a table (often handling sort specs for a single column, occasionally more)
162struct ImGuiTableColumnSortSpecs; // Sorting specification for one column of a table
163struct ImGuiTextBuffer; // Helper to hold and append into a text buffer (~string builder)
164struct ImGuiTextFilter; // Helper to parse and apply text filters (e.g. "aaaaa[,bbbbb][,ccccc]")
165struct ImGuiViewport; // A Platform Window (always only one in 'master' branch), in the future may represent Platform Monitor

167// Enumerations
168// - We don't use strongly typed enums much because they add constraints (can't extend in private code, can't store typed in bit fields, extra casting on iteration)
169// - Tip: Use your programming IDE navigation facilities on the names in the _central column_ below to find the actual flags/enum lists!
170// In Visual Studio IDE: CTRL+comma ("Edit.GoToAll") can follow symbols in comments, whereas CTRL+F12 ("Edit.GoToImplementation") cannot.
171// With Visual Assist installed: ALT+G ("VAssistX.GoToImplementation") can also follow symbols in comments.
172enum ImGuiKey : int; // -> enum ImGuiKey // Enum: A key identifier (ImGuiKey_XXX or ImGuiMod_XXX value)
173enum ImGuiMouseSource : int; // -> enum ImGuiMouseSource // Enum; A mouse input source identifier (Mouse, TouchScreen, Pen)
174typedef int ImGuiCol; // -> enum ImGuiCol_ // Enum: A color identifier for styling
175typedef int ImGuiCond; // -> enum ImGuiCond_ // Enum: A condition for many Set*() functions
176typedef int ImGuiDataType; // -> enum ImGuiDataType_ // Enum: A primary data type
177typedef int ImGuiDir; // -> enum ImGuiDir_ // Enum: A cardinal direction
178typedef int ImGuiMouseButton; // -> enum ImGuiMouseButton_ // Enum: A mouse button identifier (0=left, 1=right, 2=middle)
179typedef int ImGuiMouseCursor; // -> enum ImGuiMouseCursor_ // Enum: A mouse cursor shape
180typedef int ImGuiSortDirection; // -> enum ImGuiSortDirection_ // Enum: A sorting direction (ascending or descending)
181typedef int ImGuiStyleVar; // -> enum ImGuiStyleVar_ // Enum: A variable identifier for styling
182typedef int ImGuiTableBgTarget; // -> enum ImGuiTableBgTarget_ // Enum: A color target for TableSetBgColor()
183
184// Flags (declared as int for compatibility with old C++, to allow using as flags without overhead, and to not pollute the top of this file)
185// - Tip: Use your programming IDE navigation facilities on the names in the _central column_ below to find the actual flags/enum lists!
186// In Visual Studio IDE: CTRL+comma ("Edit.GoToAll") can follow symbols in comments, whereas CTRL+F12 ("Edit.GoToImplementation") cannot.
187// With Visual Assist installed: ALT+G ("VAssistX.GoToImplementation") can also follow symbols in comments.
188typedef int ImDrawFlags; // -> enum ImDrawFlags_ // Flags: for ImDrawList functions

190typedef int ImFontAtlasFlags; // -> enum ImFontAtlasFlags_ // Flags: for ImFontAtlas build
191typedef int ImGuiBackendFlags; // -> enum ImGuiBackendFlags_ // Flags: for io.BackendFlags
192typedef int ImGuiButtonFlags; // -> enum ImGuiButtonFlags_ // Flags: for InvisibleButton()
193typedef int ImGuiChildFlags; // -> enum ImGuiChildFlags_ // Flags: for BeginChild()
194typedef int ImGuiColorEditFlags; // -> enum ImGuiColorEditFlags_ // Flags: for ColorEdit4(), ColorPicker4() etc.
195typedef int ImGuiConfigFlags; // -> enum ImGuiConfigFlags_ // Flags: for io.ConfigFlags
196typedef int ImGuiComboFlags; // -> enum ImGuiComboFlags_ // Flags: for BeginCombo()
197typedef int ImGuiDragDropFlags; // -> enum ImGuiDragDropFlags_ // Flags: for BeginDragDropSource(), AcceptDragDropPayload()
198typedef int ImGuiFocusedFlags; // -> enum ImGuiFocusedFlags_ // Flags: for IsWindowFocused()
199typedef int ImGuiHoveredFlags; // -> enum ImGuiHoveredFlags_ // Flags: for IsItemHovered(), IsWindowHovered() etc.
200typedef int ImGuiInputTextFlags; // -> enum ImGuiInputTextFlags_ // Flags: for InputText(), InputTextMultiline()
201typedef int ImGuiKeyChord; // -> ImGuiKey | ImGuiMod_XXX // Flags: for storage only for now: an ImGuiKey optionally OR-ed with one or more ImGuiMod_XXX values.
202typedef int ImGuiPopupFlags; // -> enum ImGuiPopupFlags_ // Flags: for OpenPopup*(), BeginPopupContext*(), IsPopupOpen()
203typedef int ImGuiSelectableFlags; // -> enum ImGuiSelectableFlags_ // Flags: for Selectable()
204typedef int ImGuiSliderFlags; // -> enum ImGuiSliderFlags_ // Flags: for DragFloat(), DragInt(), SliderFloat(), SliderInt() etc.
205typedef int ImGuiTabBarFlags; // -> enum ImGuiTabBarFlags_ // Flags: for BeginTabBar()
206typedef int ImGuiTabItemFlags; // -> enum ImGuiTabItemFlags_ // Flags: for BeginTabItem()
207typedef int ImGuiTableFlags; // -> enum ImGuiTableFlags_ // Flags: For BeginTable()
208typedef int ImGuiTableColumnFlags; // -> enum ImGuiTableColumnFlags_// Flags: For TableSetupColumn()
209typedef int ImGuiTableRowFlags; // -> enum ImGuiTableRowFlags_ // Flags: For TableNextRow()
210typedef int ImGuiTreeNodeFlags; // -> enum ImGuiTreeNodeFlags_ // Flags: for TreeNode(), TreeNodeEx(), CollapsingHeader()
211typedef int ImGuiViewportFlags; // -> enum ImGuiViewportFlags_ // Flags: for ImGuiViewport

214// ImTexture: user data for renderer backend to identify a texture [Compile-time configurable type]
215// - To use something else than an opaque void* pointer: override with e.g. '#define ImTextureID MyTextureType*' in your imconfig.h file.
216// - This can be whatever to you want it to be! read the FAQ about ImTextureID for details.
217#ifndef ImTextureID
218typedef void* ImTextureID; // Default: store a pointer or an integer fitting in a pointer (most renderer backends are ok with that)
219#endif
220
221// ImDrawIdx: vertex index. [Compile-time configurable type]
222// - To use 16-bit indices + allow large meshes: backend need to set 'io.BackendFlags |= ImGuiBackendFlags_RendererHasVtxOffset' and handle ImDrawCmd::VtxOffset (recommended).
223// - To use 32-bit indices: override with '#define ImDrawIdx unsigned int' in your imconfig.h file.
224#ifndef ImDrawIdx
225typedef unsigned short ImDrawIdx; // Default: 16-bit (for maximum compatibility with renderer backends)
226#endif
227
228// Scalar data types
229typedef unsigned int ImGuiID;// A unique ID used by widgets (typically the result of hashing a stack of string)
230typedef signed char ImS8; // 8-bit signed integer
231typedef unsigned char ImU8; // 8-bit unsigned integer
232typedef signed short ImS16; // 16-bit signed integer
233typedef unsigned short ImU16; // 16-bit unsigned integer
234typedef signed int ImS32; // 32-bit signed integer == int
235typedef unsigned int ImU32; // 32-bit unsigned integer (often used to store packed colors)
236typedef signed long long ImS64; // 64-bit signed integer
237typedef unsigned long long ImU64; // 64-bit unsigned integer
238
239// Character types
240// (we generally use UTF-8 encoded string in the API. This is storage specifically for a decoded character used for keyboard input and display)
241typedef unsigned int ImWchar32; // A single decoded U32 character/code point. We encode them as multi bytes UTF-8 when used in strings.
242typedef unsigned short ImWchar16; // A single decoded U16 character/code point. We encode them as multi bytes UTF-8 when used in strings.
243#ifdef IMGUI_USE_WCHAR32 // ImWchar [configurable type: override in imconfig.h with '#define IMGUI_USE_WCHAR32' to support Unicode planes 1-16]
244typedef ImWchar32 ImWchar;
245#else
246typedef ImWchar16 ImWchar;
247#endif
248
249// Callback and functions types
250typedef int (*ImGuiInputTextCallback)(ImGuiInputTextCallbackData* data); // Callback function for ImGui::InputText()
251typedef void (*ImGuiSizeCallback)(ImGuiSizeCallbackData* data); // Callback function for ImGui::SetNextWindowSizeConstraints()
252typedef void* (*ImGuiMemAllocFunc)(size_t sz, void* user_data); // Function signature for ImGui::SetAllocatorFunctions()
253typedef void (*ImGuiMemFreeFunc)(void* ptr, void* user_data); // Function signature for ImGui::SetAllocatorFunctions()
254
255// ImVec2: 2D vector used to store positions, sizes etc. [Compile-time configurable type]
256// This is a frequently used type in the API. Consider using IM_VEC2_CLASS_EXTRA to create implicit cast from/to our preferred type.
257IM_MSVC_RUNTIME_CHECKS_OFF
258struct ImVec2
259{
260 float x, y;
261 constexpr ImVec2() : x(0.0f), y(0.0f) { }
262 constexpr ImVec2(float _x, float _y) : x(_x), y(_y) { }
263 float& operator[] (size_t idx) { IM_ASSERT(idx == 0 || idx == 1); return ((float*)(void*)(char*)this)[idx]; } // We very rarely use this [] operator, so the assert overhead is fine.
264 float operator[] (size_t idx) const { IM_ASSERT(idx == 0 || idx == 1); return ((const float*)(const void*)(const char*)this)[idx]; }
265#ifdef IM_VEC2_CLASS_EXTRA
266 IM_VEC2_CLASS_EXTRA // Define additional constructors and implicit cast operators in imconfig.h to convert back and forth between your math types and ImVec2.
267#endif
268};
269
270// ImVec4: 4D vector used to store clipping rectangles, colors etc. [Compile-time configurable type]
271struct ImVec4
272{
273 float x, y, z, w;
274 constexpr ImVec4() : x(0.0f), y(0.0f), z(0.0f), w(0.0f) { }
275 constexpr ImVec4(float _x, float _y, float _z, float _w) : x(_x), y(_y), z(_z), w(_w) { }
276#ifdef IM_VEC4_CLASS_EXTRA
277 IM_VEC4_CLASS_EXTRA // Define additional constructors and implicit cast operators in imconfig.h to convert back and forth between your math types and ImVec4.
278#endif
279};
280IM_MSVC_RUNTIME_CHECKS_RESTORE

289 // Context creation and access
290 // - Each context create its own ImFontAtlas by default. You may instance one yourself and pass it to CreateContext() to share a font atlas between contexts.
291 // - DLL users: heaps and globals are not shared across DLL boundaries! You will need to call SetCurrentContext() + SetAllocatorFunctions()
292 // for each static/DLL boundary you are calling from. Read "Context and Memory Allocators" section of imgui.cpp for details.
293 IMGUI_API ImGuiContext* CreateContext(ImFontAtlas* shared_font_atlas = NULL);
294 IMGUI_API void DestroyContext(ImGuiContext* ctx); // NULL = destroy current context
295
296 // Main
297 IMGUI_API ImGuiIO& GetIO(ImGuiContext* ctx); // access the IO structure (mouse/keyboard/gamepad inputs, time, various configuration options/flags)
298 IMGUI_API ImGuiStyle& GetStyle(ImGuiContext* ctx); // access the Style structure (colors, sizes). Always use PushStyleCol(), PushStyleVar() to modify style mid-frame!
299 IMGUI_API void NewFrame(ImGuiContext* ctx); // start a new Dear ImGui frame, you can submit any command from this point until Render()/EndFrame().
300 IMGUI_API void EndFrame(ImGuiContext* ctx); // ends the Dear ImGui frame. automatically called by Render(). If you don't need to render data (skipping rendering) you may call EndFrame() without Render()... but you'll have wasted CPU already! If you don't need to render, better to not create any windows and not call NewFrame() at all!
301 IMGUI_API void Render(ImGuiContext* ctx); // ends the Dear ImGui frame, finalize the draw data. You can then get call GetDrawData().
302 IMGUI_API ImDrawData* GetDrawData(ImGuiContext* ctx); // valid after Render() and until the next call to NewFrame(). this is what you have to render.
303
304 // Demo, Debug, Information
305 IMGUI_API void ShowDemoWindow(ImGuiContext* ctx, bool* p_open = NULL); // create Demo window. demonstrate most ImGui features. call this to learn about the library! try to make it always available in your application!
306 IMGUI_API void ShowMetricsWindow(ImGuiContext* ctx, bool* p_open = NULL); // create Metrics/Debugger window. display Dear ImGui internals: windows, draw commands, various internal state, etc.
307 IMGUI_API void ShowDebugLogWindow(ImGuiContext* ctx, bool* p_open = NULL); // create Debug Log window. display a simplified log of important dear imgui events.
308 IMGUI_API void ShowIDStackToolWindow(ImGuiContext* ctx, bool* p_open = NULL); // create Stack Tool window. hover items with mouse to query information about the source of their unique ID.
309 IMGUI_API void ShowAboutWindow(ImGuiContext* ctx, bool* p_open = NULL); // create About window. display Dear ImGui version, credits and build/system information.
310 IMGUI_API void ShowStyleEditor(ImGuiContext* ctx, ImGuiStyle* ref = NULL); // add style editor block (not a window). you can pass in a reference ImGuiStyle structure to compare to, revert to and save to (else it uses the default style)
311 IMGUI_API bool ShowStyleSelector(ImGuiContext* ctx, const char* label); // add style selector block (not a window), essentially a combo listing the default styles.
312 IMGUI_API void ShowFontAtlas(ImGuiContext* ctx, ImFontAtlas* atlas);
313 IMGUI_API void ShowFontSelector(ImGuiContext* ctx, const char* label); // add font selector block (not a window), essentially a combo listing the loaded fonts.
314 IMGUI_API void ShowUserGuide(ImGuiContext* ctx); // add basic help/info block (not a window): how to manipulate ImGui as an end-user (mouse/keyboard controls).
315 IMGUI_API const char* GetVersion(); // get the compiled version string e.g. "1.80 WIP" (essentially the value for IMGUI_VERSION from the compiled version of imgui.cpp)
316
317 // Styles
318 IMGUI_API void StyleColorsDark(ImGuiContext* ctx, ImGuiStyle* dst = NULL); // new, recommended style (default)
319 IMGUI_API void StyleColorsLight(ImGuiContext* ctx, ImGuiStyle* dst = NULL); // best used with borders and a custom, thicker font
320 IMGUI_API void StyleColorsClassic(ImGuiContext* ctx, ImGuiStyle* dst = NULL); // classic imgui style

322 // Windows
323 // - Begin() = push window to the stack and start appending to it. End() = pop window from the stack.
324 // - Passing 'bool* p_open != NULL' shows a window-closing widget in the upper-right corner of the window,
325 // which clicking will set the boolean to false when clicked.
326 // - You may append multiple times to the same window during the same frame by calling Begin()/End() pairs multiple times.
327 // Some information such as 'flags' or 'p_open' will only be considered by the first call to Begin().
328 // - Begin() return false to indicate the window is collapsed or fully clipped, so you may early out and omit submitting
329 // anything to the window. Always call a matching End() for each Begin() call, regardless of its return value!
330 // [Important: due to legacy reason, Begin/End and BeginChild/EndChild are inconsistent with all other functions
331 // such as BeginMenu/EndMenu, BeginPopup/EndPopup, etc. where the EndXXX call should only be called if the corresponding
332 // BeginXXX function returned true. Begin and BeginChild are the only odd ones out. Will be fixed in a future update.]
333 // - Note that the bottom of window stack always contains a window called "Debug".
334 IMGUI_API bool Begin(ImGuiContext* ctx, const char* name, bool* p_open = NULL, ImGuiWindowFlags flags = 0);
335 IMGUI_API void End(ImGuiContext* ctx);
336
337 // Child Windows
338 // - Use child windows to begin into a self-contained independent scrolling/clipping regions within a host window. Child windows can embed their own child.
339 // - Before 1.90 (November 2023), the "ImGuiChildFlags child_flags = 0" parameter was "bool border = false".
340 // This API is backward compatible with old code, as we guarantee that ImGuiChildFlags_Border == true.
341 // Consider updating your old call sites:
342 // BeginChild("Name", size, false) -> Begin("Name", size, 0); or Begin("Name", size, ImGuiChildFlags_None);
343 // BeginChild("Name", size, true) -> Begin("Name", size, ImGuiChildFlags_Border);
344 // - Manual sizing (each axis can use a different setting e.g. ImVec2(0.0f, 400.0f)):
345 // == 0.0f: use remaining parent window size for this axis.
346 // > 0.0f: use specified size for this axis.
347 // < 0.0f: right/bottom-align to specified distance from available content boundaries.
348 // - Specifying ImGuiChildFlags_AutoResizeX or ImGuiChildFlags_AutoResizeY makes the sizing automatic based on child contents.
349 // Combining both ImGuiChildFlags_AutoResizeX _and_ ImGuiChildFlags_AutoResizeY defeats purpose of a scrolling region and is NOT recommended.
350 // - BeginChild() returns false to indicate the window is collapsed or fully clipped, so you may early out and omit submitting
351 // anything to the window. Always call a matching EndChild() for each BeginChild() call, regardless of its return value.
352 // [Important: due to legacy reason, Begin/End and BeginChild/EndChild are inconsistent with all other functions
353 // such as BeginMenu/EndMenu, BeginPopup/EndPopup, etc. where the EndXXX call should only be called if the corresponding
354 // BeginXXX function returned true. Begin and BeginChild are the only odd ones out. Will be fixed in a future update.]
355 IMGUI_API bool BeginChild(ImGuiContext* ctx, const char* str_id, const ImVec2& size = ImVec2(0, 0), ImGuiChildFlags child_flags = 0, ImGuiWindowFlags window_flags = 0);
356 IMGUI_API bool BeginChild(ImGuiContext* ctx, ImGuiID id, const ImVec2& size = ImVec2(0, 0), ImGuiChildFlags child_flags = 0, ImGuiWindowFlags window_flags = 0);
357 IMGUI_API void EndChild(ImGuiContext* ctx);
358
359 // Windows Utilities
360 // - 'current window' = the window we are appending into while inside a Begin()/End() block. 'next window' = next window we will Begin() into.
361 IMGUI_API bool IsWindowAppearing(ImGuiContext* ctx);

Use the 'io.WantCaptureMouse' boolean for that! Refer to FAQ entry "How can I tell whether to dispatch mouse/keyboard to Dear ImGui or my application?" for details.

445 // Layout cursor positioning
446 // - By "cursor" we mean the current output position.
447 // - The typical widget behavior is to output themselves at the current cursor position, then move the cursor one line down.
448 // - You can call SameLine() between widgets to undo the last carriage return and output at the right of the preceding widget.
449 // - Attention! We currently have inconsistencies between window-local and absolute positions we will aim to fix with future API:
450 // - Absolute coordinate: GetCursorScreenPos(), SetCursorScreenPos(), all ImDrawList:: functions. -> this is the preferred way forward.
451 // - Window-local coordinates: SameLine(), GetCursorPos(), SetCursorPos(), GetCursorStartPos(), GetContentRegionMax(), GetWindowContentRegion*(), PushTextWrapPos()
452 // - GetCursorScreenPos() = GetCursorPos() + GetWindowPos(). GetWindowPos() is almost only ever useful to convert from window-local to absolute coordinates.
453 IMGUI_API ImVec2 GetCursorScreenPos(ImGuiContext* ctx); // cursor position in absolute coordinates (prefer using this, also more useful to work with ImDrawList API).
454 IMGUI_API void SetCursorScreenPos(ImGuiContext* ctx, const ImVec2& pos); // cursor position in absolute coordinates
455 IMGUI_API ImVec2 GetCursorPos(ImGuiContext* ctx); // [window-local] cursor position in window coordinates (relative to window position)
456 IMGUI_API float GetCursorPosX(ImGuiContext* ctx); // [window-local] "
457 IMGUI_API float GetCursorPosY(ImGuiContext* ctx); // [window-local] "
458 IMGUI_API void SetCursorPos(ImGuiContext* ctx, const ImVec2& local_pos); // [window-local] "
459 IMGUI_API void SetCursorPosX(ImGuiContext* ctx, float local_x); // [window-local] "
460 IMGUI_API void SetCursorPosY(ImGuiContext* ctx, float local_y); // [window-local] "
461 IMGUI_API ImVec2 GetCursorStartPos(ImGuiContext* ctx); // [window-local] initial cursor position, in window coordinates

479 // ID stack/scopes
480 // Read the FAQ (docs/FAQ.md or http://dearimgui.com/faq) for more details about how ID are handled in dear imgui.
481 // - Those questions are answered and impacted by understanding of the ID stack system:
482 // - "Q: Why is my widget not reacting when I click on it?"
483 // - "Q: How can I have widgets with an empty label?"
484 // - "Q: How can I have multiple widgets with the same label?"
485 // - Short version: ID are hashes of the entire ID stack. If you are creating widgets in a loop you most likely
486 // want to push a unique identifier (e.g. object pointer, loop index) to uniquely differentiate them.
487 // - You can also use the "Label##foobar" syntax within widget label to distinguish them from each others.
488 // - In this header file we use the "label"/"name" terminology to denote a string that will be displayed + used as an ID,
489 // whereas "str_id" denote a string that is only used as an ID and not normally displayed.
490 IMGUI_API void PushID(ImGuiContext* ctx, const char* str_id); // push string into the ID stack (will hash string).
491 IMGUI_API void PushID(ImGuiContext* ctx, const char* str_id_begin, const char* str_id_end); // push string into the ID stack (will hash string).
492 IMGUI_API void PushID(ImGuiContext* ctx, const void* ptr_id); // push pointer into the ID stack (will hash pointer).
493 IMGUI_API void PushID(ImGuiContext* ctx, int int_id); // push integer into the ID stack (will hash integer).
494 IMGUI_API void PopID(ImGuiContext* ctx); // pop from the ID stack.
495 IMGUI_API ImGuiID GetID(ImGuiContext* ctx, const char* str_id); // calculate unique ID (hash of whole ID stack + given parameter). e.g. if you want to query into ImGuiStorage yourself
496 IMGUI_API ImGuiID GetID(ImGuiContext* ctx, const char* str_id_begin, const char* str_id_end);
497 IMGUI_API ImGuiID GetID(ImGuiContext* ctx, const void* ptr_id);
498

545 // Widgets: Drag Sliders
546 // - CTRL+Click on any drag box to turn them into an input box. Manually input values aren't clamped by default and can go off-bounds. Use ImGuiSliderFlags_AlwaysClamp to always clamp.
547 // - For all the Float2/Float3/Float4/Int2/Int3/Int4 versions of every function, note that a 'float v[X]' function argument is the same as 'float* v',
548 // the array syntax is just a way to document the number of elements that are expected to be accessible. You can pass address of your first element out of a contiguous set, e.g. &myvector.x
549 // - Adjust format string to decorate the value with a prefix, a suffix, or adapt the editing and display precision e.g. "%.3f" -> 1.234; "%5.2f secs" -> 01.23 secs; "Biscuit: %.0f" -> Biscuit: 1; etc.
550 // - Format string may also be set to NULL or use the default format ("%f" or "%d").
551 // - Speed are per-pixel of mouse movement (v_speed=0.2f: mouse needs to move by 5 pixels to increase value by 1). For gamepad/keyboard navigation, minimum speed is Max(v_speed, minimum_step_at_given_precision).
552 // - Use v_min < v_max to clamp edits to given limits. Note that CTRL+Click manual input can override those limits if ImGuiSliderFlags_AlwaysClamp is not used.
553 // - Use v_max = FLT_MAX / INT_MAX etc to avoid clamping to a maximum, same with v_min = -FLT_MAX / INT_MIN to avoid clamping to a minimum.
554 // - We use the same sets of flags for DragXXX() and SliderXXX() functions as the features are the same and it makes it easier to swap them.
555 // - Legacy: Pre-1.78 there are DragXXX() function signatures that take a final `float power=1.0f' argument instead of the `ImGuiSliderFlags flags=0' argument.
556 // If you get a warning converting a float to ImGuiSliderFlags, read https://github.com/ocornut/imgui/issues/3361
557 IMGUI_API bool DragFloat(ImGuiContext* ctx, const char* label, float* v, float v_speed = 1.0f, float v_min = 0.0f, float v_max = 0.0f, const char* format = "%.3f", ImGuiSliderFlags flags = 0); // If v_min >= v_max we have no bound
558 IMGUI_API bool DragFloat2(ImGuiContext* ctx, const char* label, float v[2], float v_speed = 1.0f, float v_min = 0.0f, float v_max = 0.0f, const char* format = "%.3f", ImGuiSliderFlags flags = 0);
559 IMGUI_API bool DragFloat3(ImGuiContext* ctx, const char* label, float v[3], float v_speed = 1.0f, float v_min = 0.0f, float v_max = 0.0f, const char* format = "%.3f", ImGuiSliderFlags flags = 0);
560 IMGUI_API bool DragFloat4(ImGuiContext* ctx, const char* label, float v[4], float v_speed = 1.0f, float v_min = 0.0f, float v_max = 0.0f, const char* format = "%.3f", ImGuiSliderFlags flags = 0);
561 IMGUI_API bool DragFloatRange2(ImGuiContext* ctx, const char* label, float* v_current_min, float* v_current_max, float v_speed = 1.0f, float v_min = 0.0f, float v_max = 0.0f, const char* format = "%.3f", const char* format_max = NULL, ImGuiSliderFlags flags = 0);

684 // Tooltips
685 // - Tooltips are windows following the mouse. They do not take focus away.
686 // - A tooltip window can contain items of any types. SetTooltip() is a shortcut for the 'if (BeginTooltip()) { Text(...); EndTooltip(); }' idiom.
687 IMGUI_API bool BeginTooltip(ImGuiContext* ctx); // begin/append a tooltip window.
688 IMGUI_API void EndTooltip(ImGuiContext* ctx); // only call EndTooltip() if BeginTooltip()/BeginItemTooltip() returns true!
689 IMGUI_API void SetTooltip(ImGuiContext* ctx, const char* fmt, ...) IM_FMTARGS(2); // set a text-only tooltip. Often used after a ImGui::IsItemHovered() check. Override any previous call to SetTooltip().
690 IMGUI_API void SetTooltipV(ImGuiContext* ctx, const char* fmt, va_list args) IM_FMTLIST(2);
691
692 // Tooltips: helpers for showing a tooltip when hovering an item
693 // - BeginItemTooltip() is a shortcut for the 'if (IsItemHovered(ImGuiHoveredFlags_ForTooltip) && BeginTooltip())' idiom.
694 // - SetItemTooltip() is a shortcut for the 'if (IsItemHovered(ImGuiHoveredFlags_ForTooltip)) { SetTooltip(...); }' idiom.
695 // - Where 'ImGuiHoveredFlags_ForTooltip' itself is a shortcut to use 'style.HoverFlagsForTooltipMouse' or 'style.HoverFlagsForTooltipNav' depending on active input type. For mouse it defaults to 'ImGuiHoveredFlags_Stationary | ImGuiHoveredFlags_DelayShort'.
696 IMGUI_API bool BeginItemTooltip(ImGuiContext* ctx); // begin/append a tooltip window if preceding item was hovered.
697 IMGUI_API void SetItemTooltip(ImGuiContext* ctx, const char* fmt, ...) IM_FMTARGS(2); // set a text-only tooltip if preceeding item was hovered. override any previous call to SetTooltip().
698 IMGUI_API void SetItemTooltipV(ImGuiContext* ctx, const char* fmt, va_list args) IM_FMTLIST(2);
699
700 // Popups, Modals
701 // - They block normal mouse hovering detection (and therefore most mouse interactions) behind them.
702 // - If not modal: they can be closed by clicking anywhere outside them, or by pressing ESCAPE.
703 // - Their visibility state (~bool) is held internally instead of being held by the programmer as we are used to with regular Begin*() calls.
704 // - The 3 properties above are related: we need to retain popup visibility state in the library because popups may be closed as any time.
705 // - You can bypass the hovering restriction by using ImGuiHoveredFlags_AllowWhenBlockedByPopup when calling IsItemHovered() or IsWindowHovered().
706 // - IMPORTANT: Popup identifiers are relative to the current ID stack, so OpenPopup and BeginPopup generally needs to be at the same level of the stack.
707 // This is sometimes leading to confusing mistakes. May rework this in the future.
708
709 // Popups: begin/end functions
710 // - BeginPopup(): query popup state, if open start appending into the window. Call EndPopup() afterwards. ImGuiWindowFlags are forwarded to the window.
711 // - BeginPopupModal(): block every interaction behind the window, cannot be closed by user, add a dimming background, has a title bar.
712 IMGUI_API bool BeginPopup(ImGuiContext* ctx, const char* str_id, ImGuiWindowFlags flags = 0); // return true if the popup is open, and you can start outputting to it.
713 IMGUI_API bool BeginPopupModal(ImGuiContext* ctx, const char* name, bool* p_open = NULL, ImGuiWindowFlags flags = 0); // return true if the modal is open, and you can start outputting to it.
714 IMGUI_API void EndPopup(ImGuiContext* ctx); // only call EndPopup() if BeginPopupXXX() returns true!
715
716 // Popups: open/close functions
717 // - OpenPopup(): set popup state to open. ImGuiPopupFlags are available for opening options.
718 // - If not modal: they can be closed by clicking anywhere outside them, or by pressing ESCAPE.
719 // - CloseCurrentPopup(): use inside the BeginPopup()/EndPopup() scope to close manually.
720 // - CloseCurrentPopup() is called by default by Selectable()/MenuItem() when activated (FIXME: need some options).
721 // - Use ImGuiPopupFlags_NoOpenOverExistingPopup to avoid opening a popup if there's already one at the same level. This is equivalent to e.g. testing for !IsAnyPopupOpen() prior to OpenPopup().
722 // - Use IsWindowAppearing() after BeginPopup() to tell if a window just opened.
723 // - IMPORTANT: Notice that for OpenPopupOnItemClick() we exceptionally default flags to 1 (== ImGuiPopupFlags_MouseButtonRight) for backward compatibility with older API taking 'int mouse_button = 1' parameter
724 IMGUI_API void OpenPopup(ImGuiContext* ctx, const char* str_id, ImGuiPopupFlags popup_flags = 0); // call to mark popup as open (don't call every frame!).
725 IMGUI_API void OpenPopup(ImGuiContext* ctx, ImGuiID id, ImGuiPopupFlags popup_flags = 0); // id overload to facilitate calling from nested stacks
726 IMGUI_API void OpenPopupOnItemClick(ImGuiContext* ctx, const char* str_id = NULL, ImGuiPopupFlags popup_flags = 1); // helper to open popup when clicked on last item. Default to ImGuiPopupFlags_MouseButtonRight == 1. (note: actually triggers on the mouse _released_ event to be consistent with popup behaviors)
727 IMGUI_API void CloseCurrentPopup(ImGuiContext* ctx); // manually close the popup we have begin-ed into.
728
729 // Popups: open+begin combined functions helpers
730 // - Helpers to do OpenPopup+BeginPopup where the Open action is triggered by e.g. hovering an item and right-clicking.
731 // - They are convenient to easily create context menus, hence the name.
732 // - IMPORTANT: Notice that BeginPopupContextXXX takes ImGuiPopupFlags just like OpenPopup() and unlike BeginPopup(). For full consistency, we may add ImGuiWindowFlags to the BeginPopupContextXXX functions in the future.
733 // - IMPORTANT: Notice that we exceptionally default their flags to 1 (== ImGuiPopupFlags_MouseButtonRight) for backward compatibility with older API taking 'int mouse_button = 1' parameter, so if you add other flags remember to re-add the ImGuiPopupFlags_MouseButtonRight.
734 IMGUI_API bool BeginPopupContextItem(ImGuiContext* ctx, const char* str_id = NULL, ImGuiPopupFlags popup_flags = 1); // open+begin popup when clicked on last item. Use str_id==NULL to associate the popup to previous item. If you want to use that on a non-interactive item such as Text() you need to pass in an explicit ID here. read comments in .cpp!
735 IMGUI_API bool BeginPopupContextWindow(ImGuiContext* ctx, const char* str_id = NULL, ImGuiPopupFlags popup_flags = 1);// open+begin popup when clicked on current window.
736 IMGUI_API bool BeginPopupContextVoid(ImGuiContext* ctx, const char* str_id = NULL, ImGuiPopupFlags popup_flags = 1); // open+begin popup when clicked in void (where there are no windows).
737
738 // Popups: query functions
739 // - IsPopupOpen(): return true if the popup is open at the current BeginPopup() level of the popup stack.
740 // - IsPopupOpen() with ImGuiPopupFlags_AnyPopupId: return true if any popup is open at the current BeginPopup() level of the popup stack.
741 // - IsPopupOpen() with ImGuiPopupFlags_AnyPopupId + ImGuiPopupFlags_AnyPopupLevel: return true if any popup is open.
742 IMGUI_API bool IsPopupOpen(ImGuiContext* ctx, const char* str_id, ImGuiPopupFlags flags = 0); // return true if the popup is open.
743
744 // Tables
745 // - Full-featured replacement for old Columns API.
746 // - See Demo->Tables for demo code. See top of imgui_tables.cpp for general commentary.
747 // - See ImGuiTableFlags_ and ImGuiTableColumnFlags_ enums for a description of available flags.
748 // The typical call flow is:
749 // - 1. Call BeginTable(), early out if returning false.
750 // - 2. Optionally call TableSetupColumn() to submit column name/flags/defaults.
751 // - 3. Optionally call TableSetupScrollFreeze() to request scroll freezing of columns/rows.
752 // - 4. Optionally call TableHeadersRow() to submit a header row. Names are pulled from TableSetupColumn() data.
753 // - 5. Populate contents:
754 // - In most situations you can use TableNextRow() + TableSetColumnIndex(N) to start appending into a column.
755 // - If you are using tables as a sort of grid, where every column is holding the same type of contents,
756 // you may prefer using TableNextColumn() instead of TableNextRow() + TableSetColumnIndex().
757 // TableNextColumn() will automatically wrap-around into the next row if needed.
758 // - IMPORTANT: Comparatively to the old Columns() API, we need to call TableNextColumn() for the first column!
759 // - Summary of possible call flow:
760 // --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
761 // TableNextRow() -> TableSetColumnIndex(0) -> Text("Hello 0") -> TableSetColumnIndex(1) -> Text("Hello 1") // OK
762 // TableNextRow() -> TableNextColumn() -> Text("Hello 0") -> TableNextColumn() -> Text("Hello 1") // OK
763 // TableNextColumn() -> Text("Hello 0") -> TableNextColumn() -> Text("Hello 1") // OK: TableNextColumn() automatically gets to next row!
764 // TableNextRow() -> Text("Hello 0") // Not OK! Missing TableSetColumnIndex() or TableNextColumn()! Text will not appear!
765 // --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
766 // - 5. Call EndTable()
767 IMGUI_API bool BeginTable(ImGuiContext* ctx, const char* str_id, int column, ImGuiTableFlags flags = 0, const ImVec2& outer_size = ImVec2(0.0f, 0.0f), float inner_width = 0.0f);
768 IMGUI_API void EndTable(ImGuiContext* ctx); // only call EndTable() if BeginTable() returns true!
769 IMGUI_API void TableNextRow(ImGuiContext* ctx, ImGuiTableRowFlags row_flags = 0, float min_row_height = 0.0f); // append into the first cell of a new row.
770 IMGUI_API bool TableNextColumn(ImGuiContext* ctx); // append into the next column (or first column of next row if currently in last column). Return true when column is visible.
771 IMGUI_API bool TableSetColumnIndex(ImGuiContext* ctx, int column_n); // append into the specified column. Return true when column is visible.
772
773 // Tables: Headers & Columns declaration
774 // - Use TableSetupColumn() to specify label, resizing policy, default width/weight, id, various other flags etc.
775 // - Use TableHeadersRow() to create a header row and automatically submit a TableHeader() for each column.
776 // Headers are required to perform: reordering, sorting, and opening the context menu.
777 // The context menu can also be made available in columns body using ImGuiTableFlags_ContextMenuInBody.
778 // - You may manually submit headers using TableNextRow() + TableHeader() calls, but this is only useful in
779 // some advanced use cases (e.g. adding custom widgets in header row).
780 // - Use TableSetupScrollFreeze() to lock columns/rows so they stay visible when scrolled.
781 IMGUI_API void TableSetupColumn(ImGuiContext* ctx, const char* label, ImGuiTableColumnFlags flags = 0, float init_width_or_weight = 0.0f, ImGuiID user_id = 0);
782 IMGUI_API void TableSetupScrollFreeze(ImGuiContext* ctx, int cols, int rows); // lock columns/rows so they stay visible when scrolled.
783 IMGUI_API void TableHeader(ImGuiContext* ctx, const char* label); // submit one header cell manually (rarely used)
784 IMGUI_API void TableHeadersRow(ImGuiContext* ctx); // submit a row with headers cells based on data provided to TableSetupColumn() + submit context menu
785 IMGUI_API void TableAngledHeadersRow(ImGuiContext* ctx); // submit a row with angled headers for every column with the ImGuiTableColumnFlags_AngledHeader flag. MUST BE FIRST ROW.
786
787 // Tables: Sorting & Miscellaneous functions
788 // - Sorting: call TableGetSortSpecs() to retrieve latest sort specs for the table. NULL when not sorting.
789 // When 'sort_specs->SpecsDirty == true' you should sort your data. It will be true when sorting specs have
790 // changed since last call, or the first time. Make sure to set 'SpecsDirty = false' after sorting,
791 // else you may wastefully sort your data every frame!
792 // - Functions args 'int column_n' treat the default value of -1 as the same as passing the current column index.
793 IMGUI_API ImGuiTableSortSpecs* TableGetSortSpecs(ImGuiContext* ctx); // get latest sort specs for the table (NULL if not sorting). Lifetime: don't hold on this pointer over multiple frames or past any subsequent call to BeginTable().
794 IMGUI_API int TableGetColumnCount(ImGuiContext* ctx); // return number of columns (value passed to BeginTable)
795 IMGUI_API int TableGetColumnIndex(ImGuiContext* ctx); // return current column index.
796 IMGUI_API int TableGetRowIndex(ImGuiContext* ctx); // return current row index.
797 IMGUI_API const char* TableGetColumnName(ImGuiContext* ctx, int column_n = -1); // return "" if column didn't have a name declared by TableSetupColumn(). Pass -1 to use current column.
798 IMGUI_API ImGuiTableColumnFlags TableGetColumnFlags(ImGuiContext* ctx, int column_n = -1); // return column flags so you can query their Enabled/Visible/Sorted/Hovered status flags. Pass -1 to use current column.
799 IMGUI_API void TableSetColumnEnabled(ImGuiContext* ctx, int column_n, bool v);// change user accessible enabled/disabled state of a column. Set to false to hide the column. User can use the context menu to change this themselves (right-click in headers, or right-click in columns body with ImGuiTableFlags_ContextMenuInBody)
800 IMGUI_API void TableSetBgColor(ImGuiContext* ctx, ImGuiTableBgTarget target, ImU32 color, int column_n = -1); // change the color of a cell, row, or column. See ImGuiTableBgTarget_ flags for details.

832 // Drag and Drop
833 // - On source items, call BeginDragDropSource(), if it returns true also call SetDragDropPayload() + EndDragDropSource().
834 // - On target candidates, call BeginDragDropTarget(), if it returns true also call AcceptDragDropPayload() + EndDragDropTarget().
835 // - If you stop calling BeginDragDropSource() the payload is preserved however it won't have a preview tooltip (we currently display a fallback "..." tooltip, see #1725)
836 // - An item can be both drag source and drop target.
837 IMGUI_API bool BeginDragDropSource(ImGuiContext* ctx, ImGuiDragDropFlags flags = 0); // call after submitting an item which may be dragged. when this return true, you can call SetDragDropPayload() + EndDragDropSource()
838 IMGUI_API bool SetDragDropPayload(ImGuiContext* ctx, const char* type, const void* data, size_t sz, ImGuiCond cond = 0); // type is a user defined string of maximum 32 characters. Strings starting with '_' are reserved for dear imgui internal types. Data is copied and held by imgui. Return true when payload has been accepted.
839 IMGUI_API void EndDragDropSource(ImGuiContext* ctx); // only call EndDragDropSource() if BeginDragDropSource() returns true!
840 IMGUI_API bool BeginDragDropTarget(ImGuiContext* ctx); // call after submitting an item that may receive a payload. If this returns true, you can call AcceptDragDropPayload() + EndDragDropTarget()
841 IMGUI_API const ImGuiPayload* AcceptDragDropPayload(ImGuiContext* ctx, const char* type, ImGuiDragDropFlags flags = 0); // accept contents of a given type. If ImGuiDragDropFlags_AcceptBeforeDelivery is set you can peek into the payload before the mouse button is released.
842 IMGUI_API void EndDragDropTarget(ImGuiContext* ctx); // only call EndDragDropTarget() if BeginDragDropTarget() returns true!
843 IMGUI_API const ImGuiPayload* GetDragDropPayload(ImGuiContext* ctx); // peek directly into the current payload from anywhere. returns NULL when drag and drop is finished or inactive. use ImGuiPayload::IsDataType() to test for the payload type.

845 // Disabling [BETA API]
846 // - Disable all user interactions and dim items visuals (applying style.DisabledAlpha over current colors)
847 // - Those can be nested but it cannot be used to enable an already disabled section (a single BeginDisabled(true) in the stack is enough to keep everything disabled)
848 // - BeginDisabled(false) essentially does nothing useful but is provided to facilitate use of boolean expressions. If you can avoid calling BeginDisabled(False)/EndDisabled() best to avoid it.
849 IMGUI_API void BeginDisabled(ImGuiContext* ctx, bool disabled = true);
850 IMGUI_API void EndDisabled(ImGuiContext* ctx);

915 // Inputs Utilities: Keyboard/Mouse/Gamepad
916 // - the ImGuiKey enum contains all possible keyboard, mouse and gamepad inputs (e.g. ImGuiKey_A, ImGuiKey_MouseLeft, ImGuiKey_GamepadDpadUp...).
917 // - before v1.87, we used ImGuiKey to carry native/user indices as defined by each backends. About use of those legacy ImGuiKey values:
918 // - without IMGUI_DISABLE_OBSOLETE_KEYIO (legacy support): you can still use your legacy native/user indices (< 512) according to how your backend/engine stored them in io.KeysDown[], but need to cast them to ImGuiKey.
919 // - with IMGUI_DISABLE_OBSOLETE_KEYIO (this is the way forward): any use of ImGuiKey will assert with key < 512. GetKeyIndex() is pass-through and therefore deprecated (gone if IMGUI_DISABLE_OBSOLETE_KEYIO is defined).
920 IMGUI_API bool IsKeyDown(ImGuiContext* ctx, ImGuiKey key); // is key being held.
921 IMGUI_API bool IsKeyPressed(ImGuiContext* ctx, ImGuiKey key, bool repeat = true); // was key pressed (went from !Down to Down)? if repeat=true, uses io.KeyRepeatDelay / KeyRepeatRate
922 IMGUI_API bool IsKeyReleased(ImGuiContext* ctx, ImGuiKey key); // was key released (went from Down to !Down)?
923 IMGUI_API bool IsKeyChordPressed(ImGuiContext* ctx, ImGuiKeyChord key_chord); // was key chord (mods + key) pressed, e.g. you can pass 'ImGuiMod_Ctrl | ImGuiKey_S' as a key-chord. This doesn't do any routing or focus check, please consider using Shortcut() function instead.
924 IMGUI_API int GetKeyPressedAmount(ImGuiContext* ctx, ImGuiKey key, float repeat_delay, float rate); // uses provided repeat rate/delay. return a count, most often 0 or 1 but might be >1 if RepeatRate is small enough that DeltaTime > RepeatRate
925 IMGUI_API const char* GetKeyName(ImGuiContext* ctx, ImGuiKey key); // [DEBUG] returns English name of the key. Those names a provided for debugging purpose and are not meant to be saved persistently not compared.
926 IMGUI_API void SetNextFrameWantCaptureKeyboard(ImGuiContext* ctx, bool want_capture_keyboard); // Override io.WantCaptureKeyboard flag next frame (said flag is left for your application to handle, typically when true it instructs your app to ignore inputs). e.g. force capture keyboard when your widget is being hovered. This is equivalent to setting "io.WantCaptureKeyboard = want_capture_keyboard"; after the next NewFrame() call.

981
982// Flags for ImGui::Begin()
983// (Those are per-window flags. There are shared flags in ImGuiIO: io.ConfigWindowsResizeFromEdges and io.ConfigWindowsMoveFromTitleBarOnly)
984enum ImGuiWindowFlags_
985{
986 ImGuiWindowFlags_None = 0,
987 ImGuiWindowFlags_NoTitleBar = 1 << 0, // Disable title-bar
988 ImGuiWindowFlags_NoResize = 1 << 1, // Disable user resizing with the lower-right grip
989 ImGuiWindowFlags_NoMove = 1 << 2, // Disable user moving the window
990 ImGuiWindowFlags_NoScrollbar = 1 << 3, // Disable scrollbars (window can still scroll with mouse or programmatically)
991 ImGuiWindowFlags_NoScrollWithMouse = 1 << 4, // Disable user vertically scrolling with mouse wheel. On child window, mouse wheel will be forwarded to the parent unless NoScrollbar is also set.
992 ImGuiWindowFlags_NoCollapse = 1 << 5, // Disable user collapsing window by double-clicking on it. Also referred to as Window Menu Button (e.g. within a docking node).
993 ImGuiWindowFlags_AlwaysAutoResize = 1 << 6, // Resize every window to its content every frame
994 ImGuiWindowFlags_NoBackground = 1 << 7, // Disable drawing background color (WindowBg, etc.) and outside border. Similar as using SetNextWindowBgAlpha(0.0f).
995 ImGuiWindowFlags_NoSavedSettings = 1 << 8, // Never load/save settings in .ini file
996 ImGuiWindowFlags_NoMouseInputs = 1 << 9, // Disable catching mouse, hovering test with pass through.
997 ImGuiWindowFlags_MenuBar = 1 << 10, // Has a menu-bar

1024// Flags for ImGui::BeginChild()
1025// (Legacy: bot 0 must always correspond to ImGuiChildFlags_Border to be backward compatible with old API using 'bool border = false'.
1026// About using AutoResizeX/AutoResizeY flags:
1027// - May be combined with SetNextWindowSizeConstraints() to set a min/max size for each axis (see "Demo->Child->Auto-resize with Constraints").
1028// - Size measurement for a given axis is only performed when the child window is within visible boundaries, or is just appearing.
1029// - This allows BeginChild() to return false when not within boundaries (e.g. when scrolling), which is more optimal. BUT it won't update its auto-size while clipped.
1030// While not perfect, it is a better default behavior as the always-on performance gain is more valuable than the occasional "resizing after becoming visible again" glitch.
1031// - You may also use ImGuiChildFlags_AlwaysAutoResize to force an update even when child window is not in view.
1032// HOWEVER PLEASE UNDERSTAND THAT DOING SO WILL PREVENT BeginChild() FROM EVER RETURNING FALSE, disabling benefits of coarse clipping.
1033enum ImGuiChildFlags_
1034{
1035 ImGuiChildFlags_None = 0,
1036 ImGuiChildFlags_Border = 1 << 0, // Show an outer border and enable WindowPadding. (Important: this is always == 1 == true for legacy reason)
1037 ImGuiChildFlags_AlwaysUseWindowPadding = 1 << 1, // Pad with style.WindowPadding even if no border are drawn (no padding by default for non-bordered child windows because it makes more sense)
1038 ImGuiChildFlags_ResizeX = 1 << 2, // Allow resize from right border (layout direction). Enable .ini saving (unless ImGuiWindowFlags_NoSavedSettings passed to window flags)
1039 ImGuiChildFlags_ResizeY = 1 << 3, // Allow resize from bottom border (layout direction). "
1040 ImGuiChildFlags_AutoResizeX = 1 << 4, // Enable auto-resizing width. Read "IMPORTANT: Size measurement" details above.
1041 ImGuiChildFlags_AutoResizeY = 1 << 5, // Enable auto-resizing height. Read "IMPORTANT: Size measurement" details above.
1042 ImGuiChildFlags_AlwaysAutoResize = 1 << 6, // Combined with AutoResizeX/AutoResizeY. Always measure size even when child is hidden, always return true, always disable clipping optimization! NOT RECOMMENDED.
1043 ImGuiChildFlags_FrameStyle = 1 << 7, // Style the child window like a framed item: use FrameBg, FrameRounding, FrameBorderSize, FramePadding instead of ChildBg, ChildRounding, ChildBorderSize, WindowPadding.
1044};

1104// Flags for OpenPopup*(), BeginPopupContext*(), IsPopupOpen() functions.
1105// - To be backward compatible with older API which took an 'int mouse_button = 1' argument, we need to treat
1106// small flags values as a mouse button index, so we encode the mouse button in the first few bits of the flags.
1107// It is therefore guaranteed to be legal to pass a mouse button index in ImGuiPopupFlags.
1108// - For the same reason, we exceptionally default the ImGuiPopupFlags argument of BeginPopupContextXXX functions to 1 instead of 0.
1109// IMPORTANT: because the default parameter is 1 (==ImGuiPopupFlags_MouseButtonRight), if you rely on the default parameter
1110// and want to use another flag, you need to pass in the ImGuiPopupFlags_MouseButtonRight flag explicitly.
1111// - Multiple buttons currently cannot be combined/or-ed in those functions (we could allow it later).
1112enum ImGuiPopupFlags_
1113{
1114 ImGuiPopupFlags_None = 0,
1115 ImGuiPopupFlags_MouseButtonLeft = 0, // For BeginPopupContext*(): open on Left Mouse release. Guaranteed to always be == 0 (same as ImGuiMouseButton_Left)
1116 ImGuiPopupFlags_MouseButtonRight = 1, // For BeginPopupContext*(): open on Right Mouse release. Guaranteed to always be == 1 (same as ImGuiMouseButton_Right)
1117 ImGuiPopupFlags_MouseButtonMiddle = 2, // For BeginPopupContext*(): open on Middle Mouse release. Guaranteed to always be == 2 (same as ImGuiMouseButton_Middle)
1118 ImGuiPopupFlags_MouseButtonMask_ = 0x1F,
1119 ImGuiPopupFlags_MouseButtonDefault_ = 1,
1120 ImGuiPopupFlags_NoOpenOverExistingPopup = 1 << 5, // For OpenPopup*(), BeginPopupContext*(): don't open if there's already a popup at the same level of the popup stack
1121 ImGuiPopupFlags_NoOpenOverItems = 1 << 6, // For BeginPopupContextWindow(): don't return true when hovering items, only when hovering empty space
1122 ImGuiPopupFlags_AnyPopupId = 1 << 7, // For IsPopupOpen(): ignore the ImGuiID parameter and test for any popup.
1123 ImGuiPopupFlags_AnyPopupLevel = 1 << 8, // For IsPopupOpen(): search/test at any level of the popup stack (default test in the current level)
1124 ImGuiPopupFlags_AnyPopup = ImGuiPopupFlags_AnyPopupId | ImGuiPopupFlags_AnyPopupLevel,
1125};

1187// Flags for ImGui::BeginTable()
1188// - Important! Sizing policies have complex and subtle side effects, much more so than you would expect.
1189// Read comments/demos carefully + experiment with live demos to get acquainted with them.
1190// - The DEFAULT sizing policies are:
1191// - Default to ImGuiTableFlags_SizingFixedFit if ScrollX is on, or if host window has ImGuiWindowFlags_AlwaysAutoResize.
1192// - Default to ImGuiTableFlags_SizingStretchSame if ScrollX is off.
1193// - When ScrollX is off:
1194// - Table defaults to ImGuiTableFlags_SizingStretchSame -> all Columns defaults to ImGuiTableColumnFlags_WidthStretch with same weight.
1195// - Columns sizing policy allowed: Stretch (default), Fixed/Auto.
1196// - Fixed Columns (if any) will generally obtain their requested width (unless the table cannot fit them all).
1197// - Stretch Columns will share the remaining width according to their respective weight.
1198// - Mixed Fixed/Stretch columns is possible but has various side-effects on resizing behaviors.
1199// The typical use of mixing sizing policies is: any number of LEADING Fixed columns, followed by one or two TRAILING Stretch columns.
1200// (this is because the visible order of columns have subtle but necessary effects on how they react to manual resizing).
1201// - When ScrollX is on:
1202// - Table defaults to ImGuiTableFlags_SizingFixedFit -> all Columns defaults to ImGuiTableColumnFlags_WidthFixed
1203// - Columns sizing policy allowed: Fixed/Auto mostly.
1204// - Fixed Columns can be enlarged as needed. Table will show a horizontal scrollbar if needed.
1205// - When using auto-resizing (non-resizable) fixed columns, querying the content width to use item right-alignment e.g. SetNextItemWidth(-FLT_MIN) doesn't make sense, would create a feedback loop.
1206// - Using Stretch columns OFTEN DOES NOT MAKE SENSE if ScrollX is on, UNLESS you have specified a value for 'inner_width' in BeginTable().
1207// If you specify a value for 'inner_width' then effectively the scrolling space is known and Stretch or mixed Fixed/Stretch columns become meaningful again.
1208// - Read on documentation at the top of imgui_tables.cpp for details.
1209enum ImGuiTableFlags_
1210{
1211 // Features
1212 ImGuiTableFlags_None = 0,
1213 ImGuiTableFlags_Resizable = 1 << 0, // Enable resizing columns.
1214 ImGuiTableFlags_Reorderable = 1 << 1, // Enable reordering columns in header row (need calling TableSetupColumn() + TableHeadersRow() to display headers)
1215 ImGuiTableFlags_Hideable = 1 << 2, // Enable hiding/disabling columns in context menu.
1216 ImGuiTableFlags_Sortable = 1 << 3, // Enable sorting. Call TableGetSortSpecs() to obtain sort specs. Also see ImGuiTableFlags_SortMulti and ImGuiTableFlags_SortTristate.
1217 ImGuiTableFlags_NoSavedSettings = 1 << 4, // Disable persisting columns order, width and sort settings in the .ini file.
1218 ImGuiTableFlags_ContextMenuInBody = 1 << 5, // Right-click on columns body/contents will display table context menu. By default it is available in TableHeadersRow().
1219 // Decorations
1220 ImGuiTableFlags_RowBg = 1 << 6, // Set each RowBg color with ImGuiCol_TableRowBg or ImGuiCol_TableRowBgAlt (equivalent of calling TableSetBgColor with ImGuiTableBgFlags_RowBg0 on each row manually)
1221 ImGuiTableFlags_BordersInnerH = 1 << 7, // Draw horizontal borders between rows.
1222 ImGuiTableFlags_BordersOuterH = 1 << 8, // Draw horizontal borders at the top and bottom.
1223 ImGuiTableFlags_BordersInnerV = 1 << 9, // Draw vertical borders between columns.
1224 ImGuiTableFlags_BordersOuterV = 1 << 10, // Draw vertical borders on the left and right sides.
1225 ImGuiTableFlags_BordersH = ImGuiTableFlags_BordersInnerH | ImGuiTableFlags_BordersOuterH, // Draw horizontal borders.
1226 ImGuiTableFlags_BordersV = ImGuiTableFlags_BordersInnerV | ImGuiTableFlags_BordersOuterV, // Draw vertical borders.
1227 ImGuiTableFlags_BordersInner = ImGuiTableFlags_BordersInnerV | ImGuiTableFlags_BordersInnerH, // Draw inner borders.
1228 ImGuiTableFlags_BordersOuter = ImGuiTableFlags_BordersOuterV | ImGuiTableFlags_BordersOuterH, // Draw outer borders.
1229 ImGuiTableFlags_Borders = ImGuiTableFlags_BordersInner | ImGuiTableFlags_BordersOuter, // Draw all borders.
1230 ImGuiTableFlags_NoBordersInBody = 1 << 11, // [ALPHA] Disable vertical borders in columns Body (borders will always appear in Headers). -> May move to style
1231 ImGuiTableFlags_NoBordersInBodyUntilResize = 1 << 12, // [ALPHA] Disable vertical borders in columns Body until hovered for resize (borders will always appear in Headers). -> May move to style
1232 // Sizing Policy (read above for defaults)
1233 ImGuiTableFlags_SizingFixedFit = 1 << 13, // Columns default to _WidthFixed or _WidthAuto (if resizable or not resizable), matching contents width.
1234 ImGuiTableFlags_SizingFixedSame = 2 << 13, // Columns default to _WidthFixed or _WidthAuto (if resizable or not resizable), matching the maximum contents width of all columns. Implicitly enable ImGuiTableFlags_NoKeepColumnsVisible.
1235 ImGuiTableFlags_SizingStretchProp = 3 << 13, // Columns default to _WidthStretch with default weights proportional to each columns contents widths.
1236 ImGuiTableFlags_SizingStretchSame = 4 << 13, // Columns default to _WidthStretch with default weights all equal, unless overridden by TableSetupColumn().
1237 // Sizing Extra Options
1238 ImGuiTableFlags_NoHostExtendX = 1 << 16, // Make outer width auto-fit to columns, overriding outer_size.x value. Only available when ScrollX/ScrollY are disabled and Stretch columns are not used.
1239 ImGuiTableFlags_NoHostExtendY = 1 << 17, // Make outer height stop exactly at outer_size.y (prevent auto-extending table past the limit). Only available when ScrollX/ScrollY are disabled. Data below the limit will be clipped and not visible.
1240 ImGuiTableFlags_NoKeepColumnsVisible = 1 << 18, // Disable keeping column always minimally visible when ScrollX is off and table gets too small. Not recommended if columns are resizable.
1241 ImGuiTableFlags_PreciseWidths = 1 << 19, // Disable distributing remainder width to stretched columns (width allocation on a 100-wide table with 3 columns: Without this flag: 33,33,34. With this flag: 33,33,33). With larger number of columns, resizing will appear to be less smooth.
1242 // Clipping
1243 ImGuiTableFlags_NoClip = 1 << 20, // Disable clipping rectangle for every individual columns (reduce draw command count, items will be able to overflow into other columns). Generally incompatible with TableSetupScrollFreeze().
1244 // Padding
1245 ImGuiTableFlags_PadOuterX = 1 << 21, // Default if BordersOuterV is on. Enable outermost padding. Generally desirable if you have headers.
1246 ImGuiTableFlags_NoPadOuterX = 1 << 22, // Default if BordersOuterV is off. Disable outermost padding.
1247 ImGuiTableFlags_NoPadInnerX = 1 << 23, // Disable inner padding between columns (double inner padding if BordersOuterV is on, single inner padding if BordersOuterV is off).
1248 // Scrolling
1249 ImGuiTableFlags_ScrollX = 1 << 24, // Enable horizontal scrolling. Require 'outer_size' parameter of BeginTable() to specify the container size. Changes default sizing policy. Because this creates a child window, ScrollY is currently generally recommended when using ScrollX.
1250 ImGuiTableFlags_ScrollY = 1 << 25, // Enable vertical scrolling. Require 'outer_size' parameter of BeginTable() to specify the container size.
1251 // Sorting
1252 ImGuiTableFlags_SortMulti = 1 << 26, // Hold shift when clicking headers to sort on multiple column. TableGetSortSpecs() may return specs where (SpecsCount > 1).
1253 ImGuiTableFlags_SortTristate = 1 << 27, // Allow no sorting, disable default sorting. TableGetSortSpecs() may return specs where (SpecsCount == 0).
1254 // Miscellaneous
1255 ImGuiTableFlags_HighlightHoveredColumn = 1 << 28, // Highlight column headers when hovered (may evolve into a fuller highlight)
1256
1257 // [Internal] Combinations and masks
1258 ImGuiTableFlags_SizingMask_ = ImGuiTableFlags_SizingFixedFit | ImGuiTableFlags_SizingFixedSame | ImGuiTableFlags_SizingStretchProp | ImGuiTableFlags_SizingStretchSame,
1259};

1261// Flags for ImGui::TableSetupColumn()
1262enum ImGuiTableColumnFlags_
1263{
1264 // Input configuration flags
1265 ImGuiTableColumnFlags_None = 0,
1266 ImGuiTableColumnFlags_Disabled = 1 << 0, // Overriding/master disable flag: hide column, won't show in context menu (unlike calling TableSetColumnEnabled() which manipulates the user accessible state)
1267 ImGuiTableColumnFlags_DefaultHide = 1 << 1, // Default as a hidden/disabled column.
1268 ImGuiTableColumnFlags_DefaultSort = 1 << 2, // Default as a sorting column.
1269 ImGuiTableColumnFlags_WidthStretch = 1 << 3, // Column will stretch. Preferable with horizontal scrolling disabled (default if table sizing policy is _SizingStretchSame or _SizingStretchProp).
1270 ImGuiTableColumnFlags_WidthFixed = 1 << 4, // Column will not stretch. Preferable with horizontal scrolling enabled (default if table sizing policy is _SizingFixedFit and table is resizable).
1271 ImGuiTableColumnFlags_NoResize = 1 << 5, // Disable manual resizing.
1272 ImGuiTableColumnFlags_NoReorder = 1 << 6, // Disable manual reordering this column, this will also prevent other columns from crossing over this column.
1273 ImGuiTableColumnFlags_NoHide = 1 << 7, // Disable ability to hide/disable this column.
1274 ImGuiTableColumnFlags_NoClip = 1 << 8, // Disable clipping for this column (all NoClip columns will render in a same draw command).
1275 ImGuiTableColumnFlags_NoSort = 1 << 9, // Disable ability to sort on this field (even if ImGuiTableFlags_Sortable is set on the table).
1276 ImGuiTableColumnFlags_NoSortAscending = 1 << 10, // Disable ability to sort in the ascending direction.
1277 ImGuiTableColumnFlags_NoSortDescending = 1 << 11, // Disable ability to sort in the descending direction.

1281 ImGuiTableColumnFlags_PreferSortDescending = 1 << 15, // Make the initial sort direction Descending when first sorting on this column.

1284 ImGuiTableColumnFlags_AngledHeader = 1 << 18, // TableHeadersRow() will submit an angled header row for this column. Note this will add an extra row.
1285
1286 // Output status flags, read-only via TableGetColumnFlags()
1287 ImGuiTableColumnFlags_IsEnabled = 1 << 24, // Status: is enabled == not hidden by user/api (referred to as "Hide" in _DefaultHide and _NoHide) flags.
1288 ImGuiTableColumnFlags_IsVisible = 1 << 25, // Status: is visible == is enabled AND not clipped by scrolling.
1289 ImGuiTableColumnFlags_IsSorted = 1 << 26, // Status: is currently part of the sort specs

1300enum ImGuiTableRowFlags_

1306// Enum for ImGui::TableSetBgColor()
1307// Background colors are rendering in 3 layers:
1308// - Layer 0: draw with RowBg0 color if set, otherwise draw with ColumnBg0 if set.
1309// - Layer 1: draw with RowBg1 color if set, otherwise draw with ColumnBg1 if set.
1310// - Layer 2: draw with CellBg color if set.
1311// The purpose of the two row/columns layers is to let you decide if a background color change should override or blend with the existing color.
1312// When using ImGuiTableFlags_RowBg on the table, each row has the RowBg0 color automatically set for odd/even rows.
1313// If you set the color of RowBg0 target, your color will override the existing RowBg0 color.
1314// If you set the color of RowBg1 or ColumnBg1 target, your color will blend over the RowBg0 color.
1315enum ImGuiTableBgTarget_
1316{
1317 ImGuiTableBgTarget_None = 0,
1318 ImGuiTableBgTarget_RowBg0 = 1, // Set row background color 0 (generally used for background, automatically set when ImGuiTableFlags_RowBg is used)
1319 ImGuiTableBgTarget_RowBg1 = 2, // Set row background color 1 (generally used for selection marking)
1320 ImGuiTableBgTarget_CellBg = 3, // Set cell background color (top-most color)
1321};

1326 ImGuiFocusedFlags_None = 0,
1327 ImGuiFocusedFlags_ChildWindows = 1 << 0, // Return true if any children of the window is focused
1328 ImGuiFocusedFlags_RootWindow = 1 << 1, // Test from root window (top most parent of the current hierarchy)
1329 ImGuiFocusedFlags_AnyWindow = 1 << 2, // Return true if any window is focused. Important: If you are trying to tell how to dispatch your low-level inputs, do NOT use this. Use 'io.WantCaptureMouse' instead! Please read the FAQ!
1330 ImGuiFocusedFlags_NoPopupHierarchy = 1 << 3, // Do not consider popup hierarchy (do not treat popup emitter as parent of popup) (when used with _ChildWindows or _RootWindow)
1331 //ImGuiFocusedFlags_DockHierarchy = 1 << 4, // Consider docking hierarchy (treat dockspace host as parent of docked window) (when used with _ChildWindows or _RootWindow)

1333};

1355 ImGuiHoveredFlags_RootAndChildWindows = ImGuiHoveredFlags_RootWindow | ImGuiHoveredFlags_ChildWindows,

1357 // Tooltips mode
1358 // - typically used in IsItemHovered() + SetTooltip() sequence.
1359 // - this is a shortcut to pull flags from 'style.HoverFlagsForTooltipMouse' or 'style.HoverFlagsForTooltipNav' where you can reconfigure desired behavior.
1360 // e.g. 'TooltipHoveredFlagsForMouse' defaults to 'ImGuiHoveredFlags_Stationary | ImGuiHoveredFlags_DelayShort'.
1361 // - for frequently actioned or hovered items providing a tooltip, you want may to use ImGuiHoveredFlags_ForTooltip (stationary + delay) so the tooltip doesn't show too often.
1362 // - for items which main purpose is to be hovered, or items with low affordance, or in less consistent apps, prefer no delay or shorter delay.
1363 ImGuiHoveredFlags_ForTooltip = 1 << 12, // Shortcut for standard flags when using IsItemHovered() + SetTooltip() sequence.
1364
1365 // (Advanced) Mouse Hovering delays.
1366 // - generally you can use ImGuiHoveredFlags_ForTooltip to use application-standardized flags.
1367 // - use those if you need specific overrides.
1368 ImGuiHoveredFlags_Stationary = 1 << 13, // Require mouse to be stationary for style.HoverStationaryDelay (~0.15 sec) _at least one time_. After this, can move on same item/window. Using the stationary test tends to reduces the need for a long delay.
1369 ImGuiHoveredFlags_DelayNone = 1 << 14, // IsItemHovered() only: Return true immediately (default). As this is the default you generally ignore this.
1370 ImGuiHoveredFlags_DelayShort = 1 << 15, // IsItemHovered() only: Return true after style.HoverDelayShort elapsed (~0.15 sec) (shared between items) + requires mouse to be stationary for style.HoverStationaryDelay (once per item).
1371 ImGuiHoveredFlags_DelayNormal = 1 << 16, // IsItemHovered() only: Return true after style.HoverDelayNormal elapsed (~0.40 sec) (shared between items) + requires mouse to be stationary for style.HoverStationaryDelay (once per item).
1372 ImGuiHoveredFlags_NoSharedDelay = 1 << 17, // IsItemHovered() only: Disable shared delay system where moving from one item to the next keeps the previous timer for a short time (standard for tooltips with long delays)
1373};

1535 // Keyboard Modifiers (explicitly submitted by backend via AddKeyEvent() calls)
1536 // - This is mirroring the data also written to io.KeyCtrl, io.KeyShift, io.KeyAlt, io.KeySuper, in a format allowing
1537 // them to be accessed via standard key API, allowing calls such as IsKeyPressed(), IsKeyReleased(), querying duration etc.
1538 // - Code polling every key (e.g. an interface to detect a key press for input mapping) might want to ignore those
1539 // and prefer using the real keys (e.g. ImGuiKey_LeftCtrl, ImGuiKey_RightCtrl instead of ImGuiMod_Ctrl).
1540 // - In theory the value of keyboard modifiers should be roughly equivalent to a logical or of the equivalent left/right keys.
1541 // In practice: it's complicated; mods are often provided from different sources. Keyboard layout, IME, sticky keys and
1542 // backends tend to interfere and break that equivalence. The safer decision is to relay that ambiguity down to the end-user...
1543 ImGuiMod_None = 0,
1544 ImGuiMod_Ctrl = 1 << 12, // Ctrl
1545 ImGuiMod_Shift = 1 << 13, // Shift
1546 ImGuiMod_Alt = 1 << 14, // Option/Menu
1547 ImGuiMod_Super = 1 << 15, // Cmd/Super/Windows
1548 ImGuiMod_Shortcut = 1 << 11, // Alias for Ctrl (non-macOS) _or_ Super (macOS).
1549 ImGuiMod_Mask_ = 0xF800, // 5-bits
1550
1551 // [Internal] Prior to 1.87 we required user to fill io.KeysDown[512] using their own native index + the io.KeyMap[] array.
1552 // We are ditching this method but keeping a legacy path for user code doing e.g. IsKeyPressed(MY_NATIVE_KEY_CODE)
1553 // If you need to iterate all keys (for e.g. an input mapper) you may use ImGuiKey_NamedKey_BEGIN..ImGuiKey_NamedKey_END.
1554 ImGuiKey_NamedKey_BEGIN = 512,
1555 ImGuiKey_NamedKey_END = ImGuiKey_COUNT,
1556 ImGuiKey_NamedKey_COUNT = ImGuiKey_NamedKey_END - ImGuiKey_NamedKey_BEGIN,
1557#ifdef IMGUI_DISABLE_OBSOLETE_KEYIO
1558 ImGuiKey_KeysData_SIZE = ImGuiKey_NamedKey_COUNT, // Size of KeysData[]: only hold named keys
1559 ImGuiKey_KeysData_OFFSET = ImGuiKey_NamedKey_BEGIN, // Accesses to io.KeysData[] must use (key - ImGuiKey_KeysData_OFFSET) index.
1560#else
1561 ImGuiKey_KeysData_SIZE = ImGuiKey_COUNT, // Size of KeysData[]: hold legacy 0..512 keycodes + named keys
1562 ImGuiKey_KeysData_OFFSET = 0, // Accesses to io.KeysData[] must use (key - ImGuiKey_KeysData_OFFSET) index.
1563#endif
1564
1565#ifndef IMGUI_DISABLE_OBSOLETE_FUNCTIONS
1566 ImGuiKey_ModCtrl = ImGuiMod_Ctrl, ImGuiKey_ModShift = ImGuiMod_Shift, ImGuiKey_ModAlt = ImGuiMod_Alt, ImGuiKey_ModSuper = ImGuiMod_Super, // Renamed in 1.89
1567 ImGuiKey_KeyPadEnter = ImGuiKey_KeypadEnter, // Renamed in 1.87
1568#endif
1569};

1583// Configuration flags stored in io.ConfigFlags. Set by user/application.
1584enum ImGuiConfigFlags_
1585{
1586 ImGuiConfigFlags_None = 0,
1587 ImGuiConfigFlags_NavEnableKeyboard = 1 << 0, // Master keyboard navigation enable flag. Enable full Tabbing + directional arrows + space/enter to activate.
1588 ImGuiConfigFlags_NavEnableGamepad = 1 << 1, // Master gamepad navigation enable flag. Backend also needs to set ImGuiBackendFlags_HasGamepad.
1589 ImGuiConfigFlags_NavEnableSetMousePos = 1 << 2, // Instruct navigation to move the mouse cursor. May be useful on TV/console systems where moving a virtual mouse is awkward. Will update io.MousePos and set io.WantSetMousePos=true. If enabled you MUST honor io.WantSetMousePos requests in your backend, otherwise ImGui will react as if the mouse is jumping around back and forth.
1590 ImGuiConfigFlags_NavNoCaptureKeyboard = 1 << 3, // Instruct navigation to not set the io.WantCaptureKeyboard flag when io.NavActive is set.
1591 ImGuiConfigFlags_NoMouse = 1 << 4, // Instruct imgui to clear mouse position/buttons in NewFrame(). This allows ignoring the mouse information set by the backend.
1592 ImGuiConfigFlags_NoMouseCursorChange = 1 << 5, // Instruct backend to not alter mouse cursor shape and visibility. Use if the backend cursor changes are interfering with yours and you don't want to use SetMouseCursor() to change mouse cursor. You may want to honor requests from imgui by reading GetMouseCursor() yourself instead.
1593
1594 // User storage (to allow your backend/engine to communicate to code that may be shared between multiple projects. Those flags are NOT used by core Dear ImGui)
1595 ImGuiConfigFlags_IsSRGB = 1 << 20, // Application is SRGB-aware.
1596 ImGuiConfigFlags_IsTouchScreen = 1 << 21, // Application is using a touch screen instead of a mouse.

1810// Enumeration for AddMouseSourceEvent() actual source of Mouse Input data.
1811// Historically we use "Mouse" terminology everywhere to indicate pointer data, e.g. MousePos, IsMousePressed(), io.AddMousePosEvent()
1812// But that "Mouse" data can come from different source which occasionally may be useful for application to know about.
1813// You can submit a change of pointer type using io.AddMouseSourceEvent().
1814enum ImGuiMouseSource : int
1815{
1816 ImGuiMouseSource_Mouse = 0, // Input is coming from an actual mouse.
1817 ImGuiMouseSource_TouchScreen, // Input is coming from a touch screen (no hovering prior to initial press, less precise initial press aiming, dual-axis wheeling possible).
1818 ImGuiMouseSource_Pen, // Input is coming from a pressure/magnetic pen (often used in conjunction with high-sampling rates).
1819 ImGuiMouseSource_COUNT
1820};

1822// Enumeration for ImGui::SetWindow***(), SetNextWindow***(), SetNextItem***() functions
1823// Represent a condition.
1824// Important: Treat as a regular enum! Do NOT combine multiple values using binary operators! All the functions above treat 0 as a shortcut to ImGuiCond_Always.
1825enum ImGuiCond_
1826{
1827 ImGuiCond_None = 0, // No condition (always set the variable), same as _Always
1828 ImGuiCond_Always = 1 << 0, // No condition (always set the variable), same as _None
1829 ImGuiCond_Once = 1 << 1, // Set the variable once per runtime session (only the first call will succeed)
1830 ImGuiCond_FirstUseEver = 1 << 2, // Set the variable if the object/window has no persistently saved data (no entry in .ini file)
1831 ImGuiCond_Appearing = 1 << 3, // Set the variable if the object/window is appearing after being hidden/inactive (or the first time)
1832};
