1834//-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
1835// [SECTION] Helpers: Memory allocations macros, ImVector<>
1836//-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
1837
1838//-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
1839// IM_MALLOC(), IM_FREE(), IM_NEW(), IM_PLACEMENT_NEW(), IM_DELETE()
1840// We call C++ constructor on own allocated memory via the placement "new(ptr) Type()" syntax.
1841// Defining a custom placement new() with a custom parameter allows us to bypass including <new> which on some platforms complains when user has disabled exceptions.
1842//-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
1843
1844struct ImNewWrapper {};
1845inline void* operator new(size_t, ImNewWrapper, void* ptr) { return ptr; }
1846inline void operator delete(void*, ImNewWrapper, void*) {} // This is only required so we can use the symmetrical new()
1847#define IM_ALLOC(_SIZE) ImGui::MemAlloc(_SIZE)
1848#define IM_FREE(_PTR) ImGui::MemFree(_PTR)
1849#define IM_PLACEMENT_NEW(_PTR) new(ImNewWrapper(), _PTR)
1850#define IM_NEW(_TYPE) new(ImNewWrapper(), ImGui::MemAlloc(sizeof(_TYPE))) _TYPE
1851template<typename T> void IM_DELETE(T* p) { if (p) { p->~T(); ImGui::MemFree(p); } }
1852
1853//-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
1854// ImVector<>
1855// Lightweight std::vector<>-like class to avoid dragging dependencies (also, some implementations of STL with debug enabled are absurdly slow, we bypass it so our code runs fast in debug).
1856//-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
1857// - You generally do NOT need to care or use this ever. But we need to make it available in imgui.h because some of our public structures are relying on it.
1858// - We use std-like naming convention here, which is a little unusual for this codebase.
1859// - Important: clear() frees memory, resize(0) keep the allocated buffer. We use resize(0) a lot to intentionally recycle allocated buffers across frames and amortize our costs.
1860// - Important: our implementation does NOT call C++ constructors/destructors, we treat everything as raw data! This is intentional but be extra mindful of that,
1861// Do NOT use this class as a std::vector replacement in your own code! Many of the structures used by dear imgui can be safely initialized by a zero-memset.
1862//-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
1863
1864IM_MSVC_RUNTIME_CHECKS_OFF
1865template<typename T>
1866struct ImVector
1867{
1868 int Size;
1869 int Capacity;
1870 T* Data;
1871
1872 // Provide standard typedefs but we don't use them ourselves.
1873 typedef T value_type;
1874 typedef value_type* iterator;
1875 typedef const value_type* const_iterator;
1876
1877 // Constructors, destructor
1878 inline ImVector() { Size = Capacity = 0; Data = NULL; }
1879 inline ImVector(const ImVector<T>& src) { Size = Capacity = 0; Data = NULL; operator=(src); }
1880 inline ImVector<T>& operator=(const ImVector<T>& src) { clear(); resize(src.Size); if (src.Data) memcpy(Data, src.Data, (size_t)Size * sizeof(T)); return *this; }
1881 inline ~ImVector() { if (Data) IM_FREE(Data); } // Important: does not destruct anything
1882
1883 inline void clear() { if (Data) { Size = Capacity = 0; IM_FREE(Data); Data = NULL; } } // Important: does not destruct anything
1884 inline void clear_delete() { for (int n = 0; n < Size; n++) IM_DELETE(Data[n]); clear(); } // Important: never called automatically! always explicit.
1885 inline void clear_destruct() { for (int n = 0; n < Size; n++) Data[n].~T(); clear(); } // Important: never called automatically! always explicit.
1886
1887 inline bool empty() const { return Size == 0; }
1888 inline int size() const { return Size; }
1889 inline int size_in_bytes() const { return Size * (int)sizeof(T); }
1890 inline int max_size() const { return 0x7FFFFFFF / (int)sizeof(T); }
1891 inline int capacity() const { return Capacity; }
1892 inline T& operator[](int i) { IM_ASSERT(i >= 0 && i < Size); return Data[i]; }
1893 inline const T& operator[](int i) const { IM_ASSERT(i >= 0 && i < Size); return Data[i]; }
1894
1895 inline T* begin() { return Data; }
1896 inline const T* begin() const { return Data; }
1897 inline T* end() { return Data + Size; }
1898 inline const T* end() const { return Data + Size; }
1899 inline T& front() { IM_ASSERT(Size > 0); return Data[0]; }
1900 inline const T& front() const { IM_ASSERT(Size > 0); return Data[0]; }
1901 inline T& back() { IM_ASSERT(Size > 0); return Data[Size - 1]; }
1902 inline const T& back() const { IM_ASSERT(Size > 0); return Data[Size - 1]; }
1903 inline void swap(ImVector<T>& rhs) { int rhs_size = rhs.Size; rhs.Size = Size; Size = rhs_size; int rhs_cap = rhs.Capacity; rhs.Capacity = Capacity; Capacity = rhs_cap; T* rhs_data = rhs.Data; rhs.Data = Data; Data = rhs_data; }
1904
1905 inline int _grow_capacity(int sz) const { int new_capacity = Capacity ? (Capacity + Capacity / 2) : 8; return new_capacity > sz ? new_capacity : sz; }
1906 inline void resize(int new_size) { if (new_size > Capacity) reserve(_grow_capacity(new_size)); Size = new_size; }
1907 inline void resize(int new_size, const T& v) { if (new_size > Capacity) reserve(_grow_capacity(new_size)); if (new_size > Size) for (int n = Size; n < new_size; n++) memcpy(&Data[n], &v, sizeof(v)); Size = new_size; }
1908 inline void shrink(int new_size) { IM_ASSERT(new_size <= Size); Size = new_size; } // Resize a vector to a smaller size, guaranteed not to cause a reallocation
1909 inline void reserve(int new_capacity) { if (new_capacity <= Capacity) return; T* new_data = (T*)IM_ALLOC((size_t)new_capacity * sizeof(T)); if (Data) { memcpy(new_data, Data, (size_t)Size * sizeof(T)); IM_FREE(Data); } Data = new_data; Capacity = new_capacity; }
1910 inline void reserve_discard(int new_capacity) { if (new_capacity <= Capacity) return; if (Data) IM_FREE(Data); Data = (T*)IM_ALLOC((size_t)new_capacity * sizeof(T)); Capacity = new_capacity; }
1911
1912 // NB: It is illegal to call push_back/push_front/insert with a reference pointing inside the ImVector data itself! e.g. v.push_back(v[10]) is forbidden.
1913 inline void push_back(const T& v) { if (Size == Capacity) reserve(_grow_capacity(Size + 1)); memcpy(&Data[Size], &v, sizeof(v)); Size++; }
1914 inline void pop_back() { IM_ASSERT(Size > 0); Size--; }
1915 inline void push_front(const T& v) { if (Size == 0) push_back(v); else insert(Data, v); }
1916 inline T* erase(const T* it) { IM_ASSERT(it >= Data && it < Data + Size); const ptrdiff_t off = it - Data; memmove(Data + off, Data + off + 1, ((size_t)Size - (size_t)off - 1) * sizeof(T)); Size--; return Data + off; }
1917 inline T* erase(const T* it, const T* it_last){ IM_ASSERT(it >= Data && it < Data + Size && it_last >= it && it_last <= Data + Size); const ptrdiff_t count = it_last - it; const ptrdiff_t off = it - Data; memmove(Data + off, Data + off + count, ((size_t)Size - (size_t)off - (size_t)count) * sizeof(T)); Size -= (int)count; return Data + off; }
1918 inline T* erase_unsorted(const T* it) { IM_ASSERT(it >= Data && it < Data + Size); const ptrdiff_t off = it - Data; if (it < Data + Size - 1) memcpy(Data + off, Data + Size - 1, sizeof(T)); Size--; return Data + off; }
1919 inline T* insert(const T* it, const T& v) { IM_ASSERT(it >= Data && it <= Data + Size); const ptrdiff_t off = it - Data; if (Size == Capacity) reserve(_grow_capacity(Size + 1)); if (off < (int)Size) memmove(Data + off + 1, Data + off, ((size_t)Size - (size_t)off) * sizeof(T)); memcpy(&Data[off], &v, sizeof(v)); Size++; return Data + off; }
1920 inline bool contains(const T& v) const { const T* data = Data; const T* data_end = Data + Size; while (data < data_end) if (*data++ == v) return true; return false; }
1921 inline T* find(const T& v) { T* data = Data; const T* data_end = Data + Size; while (data < data_end) if (*data == v) break; else ++data; return data; }
1922 inline const T* find(const T& v) const { const T* data = Data; const T* data_end = Data + Size; while (data < data_end) if (*data == v) break; else ++data; return data; }
1923 inline int find_index(const T& v) const { const T* data_end = Data + Size; const T* it = find(v); if (it == data_end) return -1; const ptrdiff_t off = it - Data; return (int)off; }
1924 inline bool find_erase(const T& v) { const T* it = find(v); if (it < Data + Size) { erase(it); return true; } return false; }
1925 inline bool find_erase_unsorted(const T& v) { const T* it = find(v); if (it < Data + Size) { erase_unsorted(it); return true; } return false; }
1926 inline int index_from_ptr(const T* it) const { IM_ASSERT(it >= Data && it < Data + Size); const ptrdiff_t off = it - Data; return (int)off; }
1927};
1928IM_MSVC_RUNTIME_CHECKS_RESTORE
1929
1930//-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
1931// [SECTION] ImGuiStyle
1932//-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
1933// You may modify the ImGui::GetStyle() main instance during initialization and before NewFrame().
1934// During the frame, use ImGui::PushStyleVar(ImGuiStyleVar_XXXX)/PopStyleVar() to alter the main style values,
1935// and ImGui::PushStyleColor(ImGuiCol_XXX)/PopStyleColor() for colors.
1936//-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
1937
1938struct ImGuiStyle
1939{
1940 float Alpha; // Global alpha applies to everything in Dear ImGui.
1941 float DisabledAlpha; // Additional alpha multiplier applied by BeginDisabled(). Multiply over current value of Alpha.
1942 ImVec2 WindowPadding; // Padding within a window.
1943 float WindowRounding; // Radius of window corners rounding. Set to 0.0f to have rectangular windows. Large values tend to lead to variety of artifacts and are not recommended.
1944 float WindowBorderSize; // Thickness of border around windows. Generally set to 0.0f or 1.0f. (Other values are not well tested and more CPU/GPU costly).
1945 ImVec2 WindowMinSize; // Minimum window size. This is a global setting. If you want to constrain individual windows, use SetNextWindowSizeConstraints().
1946 ImVec2 WindowTitleAlign; // Alignment for title bar text. Defaults to (0.0f,0.5f) for left-aligned,vertically centered.
1947 ImGuiDir WindowMenuButtonPosition; // Side of the collapsing/docking button in the title bar (None/Left/Right). Defaults to ImGuiDir_Left.
1948 float ChildRounding; // Radius of child window corners rounding. Set to 0.0f to have rectangular windows.
1949 float ChildBorderSize; // Thickness of border around child windows. Generally set to 0.0f or 1.0f. (Other values are not well tested and more CPU/GPU costly).
1950 float PopupRounding; // Radius of popup window corners rounding. (Note that tooltip windows use WindowRounding)
1951 float PopupBorderSize; // Thickness of border around popup/tooltip windows. Generally set to 0.0f or 1.0f. (Other values are not well tested and more CPU/GPU costly).
1952 ImVec2 FramePadding; // Padding within a framed rectangle (used by most widgets).
1953 float FrameRounding; // Radius of frame corners rounding. Set to 0.0f to have rectangular frame (used by most widgets).
1954 float FrameBorderSize; // Thickness of border around frames. Generally set to 0.0f or 1.0f. (Other values are not well tested and more CPU/GPU costly).
1955 ImVec2 ItemSpacing; // Horizontal and vertical spacing between widgets/lines.
1956 ImVec2 ItemInnerSpacing; // Horizontal and vertical spacing between within elements of a composed widget (e.g. a slider and its label).
1957 ImVec2 CellPadding; // Padding within a table cell. CellPadding.y may be altered between different rows.
1958 ImVec2 TouchExtraPadding; // Expand reactive bounding box for touch-based system where touch position is not accurate enough. Unfortunately we don't sort widgets so priority on overlap will always be given to the first widget. So don't grow this too much!
1959 float IndentSpacing; // Horizontal indentation when e.g. entering a tree node. Generally == (FontSize + FramePadding.x*2).
1960 float ColumnsMinSpacing; // Minimum horizontal spacing between two columns. Preferably > (FramePadding.x + 1).
1961 float ScrollbarSize; // Width of the vertical scrollbar, Height of the horizontal scrollbar.
1962 float ScrollbarRounding; // Radius of grab corners for scrollbar.
1963 float GrabMinSize; // Minimum width/height of a grab box for slider/scrollbar.
1964 float GrabRounding; // Radius of grabs corners rounding. Set to 0.0f to have rectangular slider grabs.
1965 float LogSliderDeadzone; // The size in pixels of the dead-zone around zero on logarithmic sliders that cross zero.
1966 float TabRounding; // Radius of upper corners of a tab. Set to 0.0f to have rectangular tabs.
1967 float TabBorderSize; // Thickness of border around tabs.
1968 float TabMinWidthForCloseButton; // Minimum width for close button to appear on an unselected tab when hovered. Set to 0.0f to always show when hovering, set to FLT_MAX to never show close button unless selected.
1969 float TabBarBorderSize; // Thickness of tab-bar separator, which takes on the tab active color to denote focus.
1970 float TableAngledHeadersAngle; // Angle of angled headers (supported values range from -50.0f degrees to +50.0f degrees).
1971 ImGuiDir ColorButtonPosition; // Side of the color button in the ColorEdit4 widget (left/right). Defaults to ImGuiDir_Right.
1972 ImVec2 ButtonTextAlign; // Alignment of button text when button is larger than text. Defaults to (0.5f, 0.5f) (centered).
1973 ImVec2 SelectableTextAlign; // Alignment of selectable text. Defaults to (0.0f, 0.0f) (top-left aligned). It's generally important to keep this left-aligned if you want to lay multiple items on a same line.
1974 float SeparatorTextBorderSize; // Thickkness of border in SeparatorText()
1975 ImVec2 SeparatorTextAlign; // Alignment of text within the separator. Defaults to (0.0f, 0.5f) (left aligned, center).
1976 ImVec2 SeparatorTextPadding; // Horizontal offset of text from each edge of the separator + spacing on other axis. Generally small values. .y is recommended to be == FramePadding.y.
1977 ImVec2 DisplayWindowPadding; // Window position are clamped to be visible within the display area or monitors by at least this amount. Only applies to regular windows.
1978 ImVec2 DisplaySafeAreaPadding; // If you cannot see the edges of your screen (e.g. on a TV) increase the safe area padding. Apply to popups/tooltips as well regular windows. NB: Prefer configuring your TV sets correctly!
1979 float MouseCursorScale; // Scale software rendered mouse cursor (when io.MouseDrawCursor is enabled). May be removed later.
1980 bool AntiAliasedLines; // Enable anti-aliased lines/borders. Disable if you are really tight on CPU/GPU. Latched at the beginning of the frame (copied to ImDrawList).
1981 bool AntiAliasedLinesUseTex; // Enable anti-aliased lines/borders using textures where possible. Require backend to render with bilinear filtering (NOT point/nearest filtering). Latched at the beginning of the frame (copied to ImDrawList).
1982 bool AntiAliasedFill; // Enable anti-aliased edges around filled shapes (rounded rectangles, circles, etc.). Disable if you are really tight on CPU/GPU. Latched at the beginning of the frame (copied to ImDrawList).
1983 float CurveTessellationTol; // Tessellation tolerance when using PathBezierCurveTo() without a specific number of segments. Decrease for highly tessellated curves (higher quality, more polygons), increase to reduce quality.
1984 float CircleTessellationMaxError; // Maximum error (in pixels) allowed when using AddCircle()/AddCircleFilled() or drawing rounded corner rectangles with no explicit segment count specified. Decrease for higher quality but more geometry.
1985 ImVec4 Colors[ImGuiCol_COUNT];
1986
1987 // Behaviors
1988 // (It is possible to modify those fields mid-frame if specific behavior need it, unlike e.g. configuration fields in ImGuiIO)
1989 float HoverStationaryDelay; // Delay for IsItemHovered(ImGuiHoveredFlags_Stationary). Time required to consider mouse stationary.
1990 float HoverDelayShort; // Delay for IsItemHovered(ImGuiHoveredFlags_DelayShort). Usually used along with HoverStationaryDelay.
1991 float HoverDelayNormal; // Delay for IsItemHovered(ImGuiHoveredFlags_DelayNormal). "
1992 ImGuiHoveredFlags HoverFlagsForTooltipMouse;// Default flags when using IsItemHovered(ImGuiHoveredFlags_ForTooltip) or BeginItemTooltip()/SetItemTooltip() while using mouse.
1993 ImGuiHoveredFlags HoverFlagsForTooltipNav; // Default flags when using IsItemHovered(ImGuiHoveredFlags_ForTooltip) or BeginItemTooltip()/SetItemTooltip() while using keyboard/gamepad.
1994
1995 IMGUI_API ImGuiStyle();
1996 IMGUI_API void ScaleAllSizes(float scale_factor);
1997};

2008struct ImGuiKeyData

2206//-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
2207// [SECTION] Misc data structures
2208//-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
2209
2210// Shared state of InputText(), passed as an argument to your callback when a ImGuiInputTextFlags_Callback* flag is used.
2211// The callback function should return 0 by default.
2212// Callbacks (follow a flag name and see comments in ImGuiInputTextFlags_ declarations for more details)
2213// - ImGuiInputTextFlags_CallbackEdit: Callback on buffer edit (note that InputText() already returns true on edit, the callback is useful mainly to manipulate the underlying buffer while focus is active)
2214// - ImGuiInputTextFlags_CallbackAlways: Callback on each iteration
2215// - ImGuiInputTextFlags_CallbackCompletion: Callback on pressing TAB
2216// - ImGuiInputTextFlags_CallbackHistory: Callback on pressing Up/Down arrows
2217// - ImGuiInputTextFlags_CallbackCharFilter: Callback on character inputs to replace or discard them. Modify 'EventChar' to replace or discard, or return 1 in callback to discard.
2218// - ImGuiInputTextFlags_CallbackResize: Callback on buffer capacity changes request (beyond 'buf_size' parameter value), allowing the string to grow.
2219struct ImGuiInputTextCallbackData
2220{
2221 ImGuiContext* Ctx; // Parent UI context
2222 ImGuiInputTextFlags EventFlag; // One ImGuiInputTextFlags_Callback* // Read-only
2223 ImGuiInputTextFlags Flags; // What user passed to InputText() // Read-only
2224 void* UserData; // What user passed to InputText() // Read-only
2225
2226 // Arguments for the different callback events
2227 // - To modify the text buffer in a callback, prefer using the InsertChars() / DeleteChars() function. InsertChars() will take care of calling the resize callback if necessary.
2228 // - If you know your edits are not going to resize the underlying buffer allocation, you may modify the contents of 'Buf[]' directly. You need to update 'BufTextLen' accordingly (0 <= BufTextLen < BufSize) and set 'BufDirty'' to true so InputText can update its internal state.
2229 ImWchar EventChar; // Character input // Read-write // [CharFilter] Replace character with another one, or set to zero to drop. return 1 is equivalent to setting EventChar=0;
2230 ImGuiKey EventKey; // Key pressed (Up/Down/TAB) // Read-only // [Completion,History]
2231 char* Buf; // Text buffer // Read-write // [Resize] Can replace pointer / [Completion,History,Always] Only write to pointed data, don't replace the actual pointer!
2232 int BufTextLen; // Text length (in bytes) // Read-write // [Resize,Completion,History,Always] Exclude zero-terminator storage. In C land: == strlen(some_text), in C++ land: string.length()
2233 int BufSize; // Buffer size (in bytes) = capacity+1 // Read-only // [Resize,Completion,History,Always] Include zero-terminator storage. In C land == ARRAYSIZE(my_char_array), in C++ land: string.capacity()+1
2234 bool BufDirty; // Set if you modify Buf/BufTextLen! // Write // [Completion,History,Always]
2235 int CursorPos; // // Read-write // [Completion,History,Always]
2236 int SelectionStart; // // Read-write // [Completion,History,Always] == to SelectionEnd when no selection)
2237 int SelectionEnd; // // Read-write // [Completion,History,Always]
2238
2239 // Helper functions for text manipulation.
2240 // Use those function to benefit from the CallbackResize behaviors. Calling those function reset the selection.
2241 IMGUI_API ImGuiInputTextCallbackData();
2242 IMGUI_API void DeleteChars(int pos, int bytes_count);
2243 IMGUI_API void InsertChars(int pos, const char* text, const char* text_end = NULL);
2244 void SelectAll() { SelectionStart = 0; SelectionEnd = BufTextLen; }
2245 void ClearSelection() { SelectionStart = SelectionEnd = BufTextLen; }
2246 bool HasSelection() const { return SelectionStart != SelectionEnd; }
2247};

2365// Helper: Key->Value storage
2366// Typically you don't have to worry about this since a storage is held within each Window.
2367// We use it to e.g. store collapse state for a tree (Int 0/1)
2368// This is optimized for efficient lookup (dichotomy into a contiguous buffer) and rare insertion (typically tied to user interactions aka max once a frame)
2369// You can use it as custom user storage for temporary values. Declare your own storage if, for example:
2370// - You want to manipulate the open/close state of a particular sub-tree in your interface (tree node uses Int 0/1 to store their state).
2371// - You want to store custom debug data easily without adding or editing structures in your code (probably not efficient, but convenient)
2372// Types are NOT stored, so it is up to you to make sure your Key don't collide with different types.
2373struct ImGuiStorage
2374{
2375 // [Internal]
2376 struct ImGuiStoragePair
2377 {
2378 ImGuiID key;
2379 union { int val_i; float val_f; void* val_p; };
2380 ImGuiStoragePair(ImGuiID _key, int _val) { key = _key; val_i = _val; }
2381 ImGuiStoragePair(ImGuiID _key, float _val) { key = _key; val_f = _val; }
2382 ImGuiStoragePair(ImGuiID _key, void* _val) { key = _key; val_p = _val; }
2383 };
2384
2385 ImVector<ImGuiStoragePair> Data;
2386
2387 // - Get***() functions find pair, never add/allocate. Pairs are sorted so a query is O(log N)
2388 // - Set***() functions find pair, insertion on demand if missing.
2389 // - Sorted insertion is costly, paid once. A typical frame shouldn't need to insert any new pair.
2390 void Clear() { Data.clear(); }
2391 IMGUI_API int GetInt(ImGuiID key, int default_val = 0) const;
2392 IMGUI_API void SetInt(ImGuiID key, int val);
2393 IMGUI_API bool GetBool(ImGuiID key, bool default_val = false) const;
2394 IMGUI_API void SetBool(ImGuiID key, bool val);
2395 IMGUI_API float GetFloat(ImGuiID key, float default_val = 0.0f) const;
2396 IMGUI_API void SetFloat(ImGuiID key, float val);
2397 IMGUI_API void* GetVoidPtr(ImGuiID key) const; // default_val is NULL
2398 IMGUI_API void SetVoidPtr(ImGuiID key, void* val);
2399
2400 // - Get***Ref() functions finds pair, insert on demand if missing, return pointer. Useful if you intend to do Get+Set.
2401 // - References are only valid until a new value is added to the storage. Calling a Set***() function or a Get***Ref() function invalidates the pointer.
2402 // - A typical use case where this is convenient for quick hacking (e.g. add storage during a live Edit&Continue session if you can't modify existing struct)
2403 // float* pvar = ImGui::GetFloatRef(key); ImGui::SliderFloat("var", pvar, 0, 100.0f); some_var += *pvar;
2404 IMGUI_API int* GetIntRef(ImGuiID key, int default_val = 0);
2405 IMGUI_API bool* GetBoolRef(ImGuiID key, bool default_val = false);
2406 IMGUI_API float* GetFloatRef(ImGuiID key, float default_val = 0.0f);
2407 IMGUI_API void** GetVoidPtrRef(ImGuiID key, void* default_val = NULL);
2408
2409 // Advanced: for quicker full rebuild of a storage (instead of an incremental one), you may add all your contents and then sort once.
2410 IMGUI_API void BuildSortByKey();
2411 // Obsolete: use on your own storage if you know only integer are being stored (open/close all tree nodes)
2412 IMGUI_API void SetAllInt(int val);
2413};

2415// Helper: Manually clip large list of items.
2416// If you have lots evenly spaced items and you have random access to the list, you can perform coarse
2417// clipping based on visibility to only submit items that are in view.
2418// The clipper calculates the range of visible items and advance the cursor to compensate for the non-visible items we have skipped.
2419// (Dear ImGui already clip items based on their bounds but: it needs to first layout the item to do so, and generally
2420// fetching/submitting your own data incurs additional cost. Coarse clipping using ImGuiListClipper allows you to easily
2421// scale using lists with tens of thousands of items without a problem)
2422// Usage:
2423// ImGuiListClipper clipper;
2424// clipper.Begin(1000); // We have 1000 elements, evenly spaced.
2425// while (clipper.Step())
2426// for (int i = clipper.DisplayStart; i < clipper.DisplayEnd; i++)
2427// ImGui::Text("line number %d", i);
2428// Generally what happens is:
2429// - Clipper lets you process the first element (DisplayStart = 0, DisplayEnd = 1) regardless of it being visible or not.
2430// - User code submit that one element.
2431// - Clipper can measure the height of the first element
2432// - Clipper calculate the actual range of elements to display based on the current clipping rectangle, position the cursor before the first visible element.
2433// - User code submit visible elements.
2434// - The clipper also handles various subtleties related to keyboard/gamepad navigation, wrapping etc.
2435struct ImGuiListClipper
2436{
2437 ImGuiContext* Ctx; // Parent UI context
2438 int DisplayStart; // First item to display, updated by each call to Step()
2439 int DisplayEnd; // End of items to display (exclusive)
2440 int ItemsCount; // [Internal] Number of items
2441 float ItemsHeight; // [Internal] Height of item after a first step and item submission can calculate it
2442 float StartPosY; // [Internal] Cursor position at the time of Begin() or after table frozen rows are all processed
2443 void* TempData; // [Internal] Internal data
2444
2445 // items_count: Use INT_MAX if you don't know how many items you have (in which case the cursor won't be advanced in the final step)
2446 // items_height: Use -1.0f to be calculated automatically on first step. Otherwise pass in the distance between your items, typically GetTextLineHeightWithSpacing() or GetFrameHeightWithSpacing().
2447 IMGUI_API ImGuiListClipper(ImGuiContext* ctx = NULL);
2448 IMGUI_API ~ImGuiListClipper();
2449 IMGUI_API void Begin(int items_count, float items_height = -1.0f);
2450 IMGUI_API void End(); // Automatically called on the last call of Step() that returns false.
2451 IMGUI_API bool Step(); // Call until it returns false. The DisplayStart/DisplayEnd fields will be set and you can process/draw those items.
2452
2453 // Call IncludeItemByIndex() or IncludeItemsByIndex() *BEFORE* first call to Step() if you need a range of items to not be clipped, regardless of their visibility.
2454 // (Due to alignment / padding of certain items it is possible that an extra item may be included on either end of the display range).
2455 inline void IncludeItemByIndex(int item_index) { IncludeItemsByIndex(item_index, item_index + 1); }
2456 IMGUI_API void IncludeItemsByIndex(int item_begin, int item_end); // item_end is exclusive e.g. use (42, 42+1) to make item 42 never clipped.
2457
2458#ifndef IMGUI_DISABLE_OBSOLETE_FUNCTIONS
2459 inline void IncludeRangeByIndices(int item_begin, int item_end) { IncludeItemsByIndex(item_begin, item_end); } // [renamed in 1.89.9]
2460 inline void ForceDisplayRangeByIndices(int item_begin, int item_end) { IncludeItemsByIndex(item_begin, item_end); } // [renamed in 1.89.6]
2461 //inline ImGuiListClipper(int items_count, float items_height = -1.0f) { memset(this, 0, sizeof(*this)); ItemsCount = -1; Begin(items_count, items_height); } // [removed in 1.79]
2462#endif
2463};
2464
2465// Helpers: ImVec2/ImVec4 operators
2466// - It is important that we are keeping those disabled by default so they don't leak in user space.
2467// - This is in order to allow user enabling implicit cast operators between ImVec2/ImVec4 and their own types (using IM_VEC2_CLASS_EXTRA in imconfig.h)
2468// - You can use '#define IMGUI_DEFINE_MATH_OPERATORS' to import our operators, provided as a courtesy.
2469#ifdef IMGUI_DEFINE_MATH_OPERATORS
2470#define IMGUI_DEFINE_MATH_OPERATORS_IMPLEMENTED
2471IM_MSVC_RUNTIME_CHECKS_OFF
2472static inline ImVec2 operator*(const ImVec2& lhs, const float rhs) { return ImVec2(lhs.x * rhs, lhs.y * rhs); }
2473static inline ImVec2 operator/(const ImVec2& lhs, const float rhs) { return ImVec2(lhs.x / rhs, lhs.y / rhs); }
2474static inline ImVec2 operator+(const ImVec2& lhs, const ImVec2& rhs) { return ImVec2(lhs.x + rhs.x, lhs.y + rhs.y); }
2475static inline ImVec2 operator-(const ImVec2& lhs, const ImVec2& rhs) { return ImVec2(lhs.x - rhs.x, lhs.y - rhs.y); }
2476static inline ImVec2 operator*(const ImVec2& lhs, const ImVec2& rhs) { return ImVec2(lhs.x * rhs.x, lhs.y * rhs.y); }
2477static inline ImVec2 operator/(const ImVec2& lhs, const ImVec2& rhs) { return ImVec2(lhs.x / rhs.x, lhs.y / rhs.y); }
2478static inline ImVec2 operator-(const ImVec2& lhs) { return ImVec2(-lhs.x, -lhs.y); }
2479static inline ImVec2& operator*=(ImVec2& lhs, const float rhs) { lhs.x *= rhs; lhs.y *= rhs; return lhs; }
2480static inline ImVec2& operator/=(ImVec2& lhs, const float rhs) { lhs.x /= rhs; lhs.y /= rhs; return lhs; }
2481static inline ImVec2& operator+=(ImVec2& lhs, const ImVec2& rhs) { lhs.x += rhs.x; lhs.y += rhs.y; return lhs; }
2482static inline ImVec2& operator-=(ImVec2& lhs, const ImVec2& rhs) { lhs.x -= rhs.x; lhs.y -= rhs.y; return lhs; }
2483static inline ImVec2& operator*=(ImVec2& lhs, const ImVec2& rhs) { lhs.x *= rhs.x; lhs.y *= rhs.y; return lhs; }
2484static inline ImVec2& operator/=(ImVec2& lhs, const ImVec2& rhs) { lhs.x /= rhs.x; lhs.y /= rhs.y; return lhs; }
2485static inline ImVec4 operator+(const ImVec4& lhs, const ImVec4& rhs) { return ImVec4(lhs.x + rhs.x, lhs.y + rhs.y, lhs.z + rhs.z, lhs.w + rhs.w); }
2486static inline ImVec4 operator-(const ImVec4& lhs, const ImVec4& rhs) { return ImVec4(lhs.x - rhs.x, lhs.y - rhs.y, lhs.z - rhs.z, lhs.w - rhs.w); }
2487static inline ImVec4 operator*(const ImVec4& lhs, const ImVec4& rhs) { return ImVec4(lhs.x * rhs.x, lhs.y * rhs.y, lhs.z * rhs.z, lhs.w * rhs.w); }
2488IM_MSVC_RUNTIME_CHECKS_RESTORE
2489#endif

2491// Helpers macros to generate 32-bit encoded colors
2492// User can declare their own format by #defining the 5 _SHIFT/_MASK macros in their imconfig file.
2493#ifndef IM_COL32_R_SHIFT
2494#ifdef IMGUI_USE_BGRA_PACKED_COLOR
2495#define IM_COL32_R_SHIFT 16
2496#define IM_COL32_G_SHIFT 8
2497#define IM_COL32_B_SHIFT 0
2498#define IM_COL32_A_SHIFT 24
2499#define IM_COL32_A_MASK 0xFF000000
2500#else
2501#define IM_COL32_R_SHIFT 0
2502#define IM_COL32_G_SHIFT 8
2503#define IM_COL32_B_SHIFT 16
2504#define IM_COL32_A_SHIFT 24
2505#define IM_COL32_A_MASK 0xFF000000
2506#endif
2507#endif
2508#define IM_COL32(R,G,B,A) (((ImU32)(A)<<IM_COL32_A_SHIFT) | ((ImU32)(B)<<IM_COL32_B_SHIFT) | ((ImU32)(G)<<IM_COL32_G_SHIFT) | ((ImU32)(R)<<IM_COL32_R_SHIFT))
2509#define IM_COL32_WHITE IM_COL32(255,255,255,255) // Opaque white = 0xFFFFFFFF
2510#define IM_COL32_BLACK IM_COL32(0,0,0,255) // Opaque black
2511#define IM_COL32_BLACK_TRANS IM_COL32(0,0,0,0) // Transparent black = 0x00000000
2512
2513// Helper: ImColor() implicitly converts colors to either ImU32 (packed 4x1 byte) or ImVec4 (4x1 float)
2514// Prefer using IM_COL32() macros if you want a guaranteed compile-time ImU32 for usage with ImDrawList API.
2515// **Avoid storing ImColor! Store either u32 of ImVec4. This is not a full-featured color class. MAY OBSOLETE.
2516// **None of the ImGui API are using ImColor directly but you can use it as a convenience to pass colors in either ImU32 or ImVec4 formats. Explicitly cast to ImU32 or ImVec4 if needed.
2517struct ImColor
2518{
2519 ImVec4 Value;
2520
2521 constexpr ImColor() { }
2522 constexpr ImColor(float r, float g, float b, float a = 1.0f) : Value(r, g, b, a) { }
2523 constexpr ImColor(const ImVec4& col) : Value(col) {}
2524 constexpr ImColor(int r, int g, int b, int a = 255) : Value((float)r * (1.0f / 255.0f), (float)g * (1.0f / 255.0f), (float)b * (1.0f / 255.0f), (float)a* (1.0f / 255.0f)) {}
2525 constexpr ImColor(ImU32 rgba) : Value((float)((rgba >> IM_COL32_R_SHIFT) & 0xFF) * (1.0f / 255.0f), (float)((rgba >> IM_COL32_G_SHIFT) & 0xFF) * (1.0f / 255.0f), (float)((rgba >> IM_COL32_B_SHIFT) & 0xFF) * (1.0f / 255.0f), (float)((rgba >> IM_COL32_A_SHIFT) & 0xFF) * (1.0f / 255.0f)) {}
2526 inline operator ImU32() const { return ImGui::ColorConvertFloat4ToU32(Value); }
2527 inline operator ImVec4() const { return Value; }
2528
2529 // FIXME-OBSOLETE: May need to obsolete/cleanup those helpers.
2530 inline void SetHSV(float h, float s, float v, float a = 1.0f){ ImGui::ColorConvertHSVtoRGB(h, s, v, Value.x, Value.y, Value.z); Value.w = a; }
2531 static ImColor HSV(float h, float s, float v, float a = 1.0f) { float r, g, b; ImGui::ColorConvertHSVtoRGB(h, s, v, r, g, b); return ImColor(r, g, b, a); }
2532};
2533
2534//-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
2535// [SECTION] Drawing API (ImDrawCmd, ImDrawIdx, ImDrawVert, ImDrawChannel, ImDrawListSplitter, ImDrawListFlags, ImDrawList, ImDrawData)
2536// Hold a series of drawing commands. The user provides a renderer for ImDrawData which essentially contains an array of ImDrawList.
2537//-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
2538
2539// The maximum line width to bake anti-aliased textures for. Build atlas with ImFontAtlasFlags_NoBakedLines to disable baking.
2540#ifndef IM_DRAWLIST_TEX_LINES_WIDTH_MAX
2541#define IM_DRAWLIST_TEX_LINES_WIDTH_MAX (63)
2542#endif
2543
2544// ImDrawCallback: Draw callbacks for advanced uses [configurable type: override in imconfig.h]
2545// NB: You most likely do NOT need to use draw callbacks just to create your own widget or customized UI rendering,
2546// you can poke into the draw list for that! Draw callback may be useful for example to:
2547// A) Change your GPU render state,
2548// B) render a complex 3D scene inside a UI element without an intermediate texture/render target, etc.
2549// The expected behavior from your rendering function is 'if (cmd.UserCallback != NULL) { cmd.UserCallback(parent_list, cmd); } else { RenderTriangles() }'
2550// If you want to override the signature of ImDrawCallback, you can simply use e.g. '#define ImDrawCallback MyDrawCallback' (in imconfig.h) + update rendering backend accordingly.
2551#ifndef ImDrawCallback
2552typedef void (*ImDrawCallback)(const ImDrawList* parent_list, const ImDrawCmd* cmd);
2553#endif
2554
2555// Special Draw callback value to request renderer backend to reset the graphics/render state.
2556// The renderer backend needs to handle this special value, otherwise it will crash trying to call a function at this address.
2557// This is useful, for example, if you submitted callbacks which you know have altered the render state and you want it to be restored.
2558// Render state is not reset by default because they are many perfectly useful way of altering render state (e.g. changing shader/blending settings before an Image call).
2559#define ImDrawCallback_ResetRenderState (ImDrawCallback)(-8)
2560
2561// Typically, 1 command = 1 GPU draw call (unless command is a callback)
2562// - VtxOffset: When 'io.BackendFlags & ImGuiBackendFlags_RendererHasVtxOffset' is enabled,
2563// this fields allow us to render meshes larger than 64K vertices while keeping 16-bit indices.
2564// Backends made for <1.71. will typically ignore the VtxOffset fields.
2565// - The ClipRect/TextureId/VtxOffset fields must be contiguous as we memcmp() them together (this is asserted for).
2566struct ImDrawCmd
2567{
2568 ImVec4 ClipRect; // 4*4 // Clipping rectangle (x1, y1, x2, y2). Subtract ImDrawData->DisplayPos to get clipping rectangle in "viewport" coordinates
2569 ImTextureID TextureId; // 4-8 // User-provided texture ID. Set by user in ImfontAtlas::SetTexID() for fonts or passed to Image*() functions. Ignore if never using images or multiple fonts atlas.
2570 unsigned int VtxOffset; // 4 // Start offset in vertex buffer. ImGuiBackendFlags_RendererHasVtxOffset: always 0, otherwise may be >0 to support meshes larger than 64K vertices with 16-bit indices.
2571 unsigned int IdxOffset; // 4 // Start offset in index buffer.
2572 unsigned int ElemCount; // 4 // Number of indices (multiple of 3) to be rendered as triangles. Vertices are stored in the callee ImDrawList's vtx_buffer[] array, indices in idx_buffer[].
2573 ImDrawCallback UserCallback; // 4-8 // If != NULL, call the function instead of rendering the vertices. clip_rect and texture_id will be set normally.
2574 void* UserCallbackData; // 4-8 // The draw callback code can access this.
2575
2576 ImDrawCmd() { memset(this, 0, sizeof(*this)); } // Also ensure our padding fields are zeroed
2577
2578 // Since 1.83: returns ImTextureID associated with this draw call. Warning: DO NOT assume this is always same as 'TextureId' (we will change this function for an upcoming feature)
2579 inline ImTextureID GetTexID() const { return TextureId; }
2580};
2581
2582// Vertex layout
2583#ifndef IMGUI_OVERRIDE_DRAWVERT_STRUCT_LAYOUT
2584struct ImDrawVert
2585{
2586 ImVec2 pos;
2587 ImVec2 uv;
2588 ImU32 col;
2589};
2590#else
2591// You can override the vertex format layout by defining IMGUI_OVERRIDE_DRAWVERT_STRUCT_LAYOUT in imconfig.h
2592// The code expect ImVec2 pos (8 bytes), ImVec2 uv (8 bytes), ImU32 col (4 bytes), but you can re-order them or add other fields as needed to simplify integration in your engine.
2593// The type has to be described within the macro (you can either declare the struct or use a typedef). This is because ImVec2/ImU32 are likely not declared at the time you'd want to set your type up.
2594// NOTE: IMGUI DOESN'T CLEAR THE STRUCTURE AND DOESN'T CALL A CONSTRUCTOR SO ANY CUSTOM FIELD WILL BE UNINITIALIZED. IF YOU ADD EXTRA FIELDS (SUCH AS A 'Z' COORDINATES) YOU WILL NEED TO CLEAR THEM DURING RENDER OR TO IGNORE THEM.
2595IMGUI_OVERRIDE_DRAWVERT_STRUCT_LAYOUT;
2596#endif
2597
2598// [Internal] For use by ImDrawList
2599struct ImDrawCmdHeader
2600{
2601 ImVec4 ClipRect;
2602 ImTextureID TextureId;
2603 unsigned int VtxOffset;
2604};
2605
2606// [Internal] For use by ImDrawListSplitter
2607struct ImDrawChannel
2608{
2609 ImVector<ImDrawCmd> _CmdBuffer;
2610 ImVector<ImDrawIdx> _IdxBuffer;
2611};

2614// Split/Merge functions are used to split the draw list into different layers which can be drawn into out of order.
2615// This is used by the Columns/Tables API, so items of each column can be batched together in a same draw call.
2616struct ImDrawListSplitter
2617{
2618 int _Current; // Current channel number (0)
2619 int _Count; // Number of active channels (1+)
2620 ImVector<ImDrawChannel> _Channels; // Draw channels (not resized down so _Count might be < Channels.Size)
2621
2622 inline ImDrawListSplitter() { memset(this, 0, sizeof(*this)); }
2623 inline ~ImDrawListSplitter() { ClearFreeMemory(); }
2624 inline void Clear() { _Current = 0; _Count = 1; } // Do not clear Channels[] so our allocations are reused next frame
2625 IMGUI_API void ClearFreeMemory();
2626 IMGUI_API void Split(ImDrawList* draw_list, int count);
2627 IMGUI_API void Merge(ImDrawList* draw_list);
2628 IMGUI_API void SetCurrentChannel(ImDrawList* draw_list, int channel_idx);
2629};
2630
2631// Flags for ImDrawList functions
2632// (Legacy: bit 0 must always correspond to ImDrawFlags_Closed to be backward compatible with old API using a bool. Bits 1..3 must be unused)
2633enum ImDrawFlags_
2634{
2635 ImDrawFlags_None = 0,
2636 ImDrawFlags_Closed = 1 << 0, // PathStroke(), AddPolyline(): specify that shape should be closed (Important: this is always == 1 for legacy reason)
2637 ImDrawFlags_RoundCornersTopLeft = 1 << 4, // AddRect(), AddRectFilled(), PathRect(): enable rounding top-left corner only (when rounding > 0.0f, we default to all corners). Was 0x01.
2638 ImDrawFlags_RoundCornersTopRight = 1 << 5, // AddRect(), AddRectFilled(), PathRect(): enable rounding top-right corner only (when rounding > 0.0f, we default to all corners). Was 0x02.
2639 ImDrawFlags_RoundCornersBottomLeft = 1 << 6, // AddRect(), AddRectFilled(), PathRect(): enable rounding bottom-left corner only (when rounding > 0.0f, we default to all corners). Was 0x04.
2640 ImDrawFlags_RoundCornersBottomRight = 1 << 7, // AddRect(), AddRectFilled(), PathRect(): enable rounding bottom-right corner only (when rounding > 0.0f, we default to all corners). Wax 0x08.
2641 ImDrawFlags_RoundCornersNone = 1 << 8, // AddRect(), AddRectFilled(), PathRect(): disable rounding on all corners (when rounding > 0.0f). This is NOT zero, NOT an implicit flag!
2642 ImDrawFlags_RoundCornersTop = ImDrawFlags_RoundCornersTopLeft | ImDrawFlags_RoundCornersTopRight,
2643 ImDrawFlags_RoundCornersBottom = ImDrawFlags_RoundCornersBottomLeft | ImDrawFlags_RoundCornersBottomRight,
2644 ImDrawFlags_RoundCornersLeft = ImDrawFlags_RoundCornersBottomLeft | ImDrawFlags_RoundCornersTopLeft,
2645 ImDrawFlags_RoundCornersRight = ImDrawFlags_RoundCornersBottomRight | ImDrawFlags_RoundCornersTopRight,
2646 ImDrawFlags_RoundCornersAll = ImDrawFlags_RoundCornersTopLeft | ImDrawFlags_RoundCornersTopRight | ImDrawFlags_RoundCornersBottomLeft | ImDrawFlags_RoundCornersBottomRight,
2647 ImDrawFlags_RoundCornersDefault_ = ImDrawFlags_RoundCornersAll, // Default to ALL corners if none of the _RoundCornersXX flags are specified.
2648 ImDrawFlags_RoundCornersMask_ = ImDrawFlags_RoundCornersAll | ImDrawFlags_RoundCornersNone,
2649};
2650
2651// Flags for ImDrawList instance. Those are set automatically by ImGui:: functions from ImGuiIO settings, and generally not manipulated directly.
2652// It is however possible to temporarily alter flags between calls to ImDrawList:: functions.
2653enum ImDrawListFlags_
2654{
2655 ImDrawListFlags_None = 0,
2656 ImDrawListFlags_AntiAliasedLines = 1 << 0, // Enable anti-aliased lines/borders (*2 the number of triangles for 1.0f wide line or lines thin enough to be drawn using textures, otherwise *3 the number of triangles)
2657 ImDrawListFlags_AntiAliasedLinesUseTex = 1 << 1, // Enable anti-aliased lines/borders using textures when possible. Require backend to render with bilinear filtering (NOT point/nearest filtering).
2658 ImDrawListFlags_AntiAliasedFill = 1 << 2, // Enable anti-aliased edge around filled shapes (rounded rectangles, circles).
2659 ImDrawListFlags_AllowVtxOffset = 1 << 3, // Can emit 'VtxOffset > 0' to allow large meshes. Set when 'ImGuiBackendFlags_RendererHasVtxOffset' is enabled.
2660};
2661
2662// Draw command list
2663// This is the low-level list of polygons that ImGui:: functions are filling. At the end of the frame,
2664// all command lists are passed to your ImGuiIO::RenderDrawListFn function for rendering.
2665// Each dear imgui window contains its own ImDrawList. You can use ImGui::GetWindowDrawList() to
2666// access the current window draw list and draw custom primitives.
2667// You can interleave normal ImGui:: calls and adding primitives to the current draw list.
2668// In single viewport mode, top-left is == GetMainViewport()->Pos (generally 0,0), bottom-right is == GetMainViewport()->Pos+Size (generally io.DisplaySize).
2669// You are totally free to apply whatever transformation matrix to want to the data (depending on the use of the transformation you may want to apply it to ClipRect as well!)
2670// Important: Primitives are always added to the list and not culled (culling is done at higher-level by ImGui:: functions), if you use this API a lot consider coarse culling your drawn objects.
2671struct ImDrawList
2672{
2673 // This is what you have to render
2674 ImVector<ImDrawCmd> CmdBuffer; // Draw commands. Typically 1 command = 1 GPU draw call, unless the command is a callback.
2675 ImVector<ImDrawIdx> IdxBuffer; // Index buffer. Each command consume ImDrawCmd::ElemCount of those
2676 ImVector<ImDrawVert> VtxBuffer; // Vertex buffer.
2677 ImDrawListFlags Flags; // Flags, you may poke into these to adjust anti-aliasing settings per-primitive.
2678
2679 // [Internal, used while building lists]
2680 unsigned int _VtxCurrentIdx; // [Internal] generally == VtxBuffer.Size unless we are past 64K vertices, in which case this gets reset to 0.
2681 ImDrawListSharedData* _Data; // Pointer to shared draw data (you can use ImGui::GetDrawListSharedData() to get the one from current ImGui context)
2682 const char* _OwnerName; // Pointer to owner window's name for debugging
2683 ImDrawVert* _VtxWritePtr; // [Internal] point within VtxBuffer.Data after each add command (to avoid using the ImVector<> operators too much)
2684 ImDrawIdx* _IdxWritePtr; // [Internal] point within IdxBuffer.Data after each add command (to avoid using the ImVector<> operators too much)
2685 ImVector<ImVec4> _ClipRectStack; // [Internal]
2686 ImVector<ImTextureID> _TextureIdStack; // [Internal]
2687 ImVector<ImVec2> _Path; // [Internal] current path building
2688 ImDrawCmdHeader _CmdHeader; // [Internal] template of active commands. Fields should match those of CmdBuffer.back().
2689 ImDrawListSplitter _Splitter; // [Internal] for channels api (note: prefer using your own persistent instance of ImDrawListSplitter!)
2690 float _FringeScale; // [Internal] anti-alias fringe is scaled by this value, this helps to keep things sharp while zooming at vertex buffer content
2691
2692 // If you want to create ImDrawList instances, pass them ImGui::GetDrawListSharedData() or create and use your own ImDrawListSharedData (so you can use ImDrawList without ImGui)
2693 ImDrawList(ImDrawListSharedData* shared_data) { memset(this, 0, sizeof(*this)); _Data = shared_data; }
2694
2695 ~ImDrawList() { _ClearFreeMemory(); }
2696 IMGUI_API void PushClipRect(const ImVec2& clip_rect_min, const ImVec2& clip_rect_max, bool intersect_with_current_clip_rect = false); // Render-level scissoring. This is passed down to your render function but not used for CPU-side coarse clipping. Prefer using higher-level ImGui::PushClipRect() to affect logic (hit-testing and widget culling)
2697 IMGUI_API void PushClipRectFullScreen();
2698 IMGUI_API void PopClipRect();
2699 IMGUI_API void PushTextureID(ImTextureID texture_id);
2700 IMGUI_API void PopTextureID();
2701 inline ImVec2 GetClipRectMin() const { const ImVec4& cr = _ClipRectStack.back(); return ImVec2(cr.x, cr.y); }
2702 inline ImVec2 GetClipRectMax() const { const ImVec4& cr = _ClipRectStack.back(); return ImVec2(cr.z, cr.w); }
2703
2704 // Primitives
2705 // - Filled shapes must always use clockwise winding order. The anti-aliasing fringe depends on it. Counter-clockwise shapes will have "inward" anti-aliasing.
2706 // - For rectangular primitives, "p_min" and "p_max" represent the upper-left and lower-right corners.
2707 // - For circle primitives, use "num_segments == 0" to automatically calculate tessellation (preferred).
2708 // In older versions (until Dear ImGui 1.77) the AddCircle functions defaulted to num_segments == 12.
2709 // In future versions we will use textures to provide cheaper and higher-quality circles.
2710 // Use AddNgon() and AddNgonFilled() functions if you need to guarantee a specific number of sides.
2711 IMGUI_API void AddLine(const ImVec2& p1, const ImVec2& p2, ImU32 col, float thickness = 1.0f);
2712 IMGUI_API void AddRect(const ImVec2& p_min, const ImVec2& p_max, ImU32 col, float rounding = 0.0f, ImDrawFlags flags = 0, float thickness = 1.0f); // a: upper-left, b: lower-right (== upper-left + size)
2713 IMGUI_API void AddRectFilled(const ImVec2& p_min, const ImVec2& p_max, ImU32 col, float rounding = 0.0f, ImDrawFlags flags = 0); // a: upper-left, b: lower-right (== upper-left + size)
2714 IMGUI_API void AddRectFilledMultiColor(const ImVec2& p_min, const ImVec2& p_max, ImU32 col_upr_left, ImU32 col_upr_right, ImU32 col_bot_right, ImU32 col_bot_left);
2715 IMGUI_API void AddQuad(const ImVec2& p1, const ImVec2& p2, const ImVec2& p3, const ImVec2& p4, ImU32 col, float thickness = 1.0f);
2716 IMGUI_API void AddQuadFilled(const ImVec2& p1, const ImVec2& p2, const ImVec2& p3, const ImVec2& p4, ImU32 col);
2717 IMGUI_API void AddTriangle(const ImVec2& p1, const ImVec2& p2, const ImVec2& p3, ImU32 col, float thickness = 1.0f);
2718 IMGUI_API void AddTriangleFilled(const ImVec2& p1, const ImVec2& p2, const ImVec2& p3, ImU32 col);
2719 IMGUI_API void AddCircle(const ImVec2& center, float radius, ImU32 col, int num_segments = 0, float thickness = 1.0f);
2720 IMGUI_API void AddCircleFilled(const ImVec2& center, float radius, ImU32 col, int num_segments = 0);
2721 IMGUI_API void AddNgon(const ImVec2& center, float radius, ImU32 col, int num_segments, float thickness = 1.0f);
2722 IMGUI_API void AddNgonFilled(const ImVec2& center, float radius, ImU32 col, int num_segments);
2723 IMGUI_API void AddEllipse(const ImVec2& center, float radius_x, float radius_y, ImU32 col, float rot = 0.0f, int num_segments = 0, float thickness = 1.0f);
2724 IMGUI_API void AddEllipseFilled(const ImVec2& center, float radius_x, float radius_y, ImU32 col, float rot = 0.0f, int num_segments = 0);
2725 IMGUI_API void AddText(const ImVec2& pos, ImU32 col, const char* text_begin, const char* text_end = NULL);
2726 IMGUI_API void AddText(const ImFont* font, float font_size, const ImVec2& pos, ImU32 col, const char* text_begin, const char* text_end = NULL, float wrap_width = 0.0f, const ImVec4* cpu_fine_clip_rect = NULL);
2727 IMGUI_API void AddPolyline(const ImVec2* points, int num_points, ImU32 col, ImDrawFlags flags, float thickness);
2728 IMGUI_API void AddConvexPolyFilled(const ImVec2* points, int num_points, ImU32 col);
2729 IMGUI_API void AddBezierCubic(const ImVec2& p1, const ImVec2& p2, const ImVec2& p3, const ImVec2& p4, ImU32 col, float thickness, int num_segments = 0); // Cubic Bezier (4 control points)
2730 IMGUI_API void AddBezierQuadratic(const ImVec2& p1, const ImVec2& p2, const ImVec2& p3, ImU32 col, float thickness, int num_segments = 0); // Quadratic Bezier (3 control points)
2731
2732 // Image primitives
2733 // - Read FAQ to understand what ImTextureID is.
2734 // - "p_min" and "p_max" represent the upper-left and lower-right corners of the rectangle.
2735 // - "uv_min" and "uv_max" represent the normalized texture coordinates to use for those corners. Using (0,0)->(1,1) texture coordinates will generally display the entire texture.
2736 IMGUI_API void AddImage(ImTextureID user_texture_id, const ImVec2& p_min, const ImVec2& p_max, const ImVec2& uv_min = ImVec2(0, 0), const ImVec2& uv_max = ImVec2(1, 1), ImU32 col = IM_COL32_WHITE);
2737 IMGUI_API void AddImageQuad(ImTextureID user_texture_id, const ImVec2& p1, const ImVec2& p2, const ImVec2& p3, const ImVec2& p4, const ImVec2& uv1 = ImVec2(0, 0), const ImVec2& uv2 = ImVec2(1, 0), const ImVec2& uv3 = ImVec2(1, 1), const ImVec2& uv4 = ImVec2(0, 1), ImU32 col = IM_COL32_WHITE);
2738 IMGUI_API void AddImageRounded(ImTextureID user_texture_id, const ImVec2& p_min, const ImVec2& p_max, const ImVec2& uv_min, const ImVec2& uv_max, ImU32 col, float rounding, ImDrawFlags flags = 0);
2739
2740 // Stateful path API, add points then finish with PathFillConvex() or PathStroke()
2741 // - Filled shapes must always use clockwise winding order. The anti-aliasing fringe depends on it. Counter-clockwise shapes will have "inward" anti-aliasing.
2742 inline void PathClear() { _Path.Size = 0; }
2743 inline void PathLineTo(const ImVec2& pos) { _Path.push_back(pos); }
2744 inline void PathLineToMergeDuplicate(const ImVec2& pos) { if (_Path.Size == 0 || memcmp(&_Path.Data[_Path.Size - 1], &pos, 8) != 0) _Path.push_back(pos); }
2745 inline void PathFillConvex(ImU32 col) { AddConvexPolyFilled(_Path.Data, _Path.Size, col); _Path.Size = 0; }
2746 inline void PathStroke(ImU32 col, ImDrawFlags flags = 0, float thickness = 1.0f) { AddPolyline(_Path.Data, _Path.Size, col, flags, thickness); _Path.Size = 0; }
2747 IMGUI_API void PathArcTo(const ImVec2& center, float radius, float a_min, float a_max, int num_segments = 0);
2748 IMGUI_API void PathArcToFast(const ImVec2& center, float radius, int a_min_of_12, int a_max_of_12); // Use precomputed angles for a 12 steps circle
2749 IMGUI_API void PathEllipticalArcTo(const ImVec2& center, float radius_x, float radius_y, float rot, float a_min, float a_max, int num_segments = 0); // Ellipse
2750 IMGUI_API void PathBezierCubicCurveTo(const ImVec2& p2, const ImVec2& p3, const ImVec2& p4, int num_segments = 0); // Cubic Bezier (4 control points)
2751 IMGUI_API void PathBezierQuadraticCurveTo(const ImVec2& p2, const ImVec2& p3, int num_segments = 0); // Quadratic Bezier (3 control points)
2752 IMGUI_API void PathRect(const ImVec2& rect_min, const ImVec2& rect_max, float rounding = 0.0f, ImDrawFlags flags = 0);
2753
2754 // Advanced
2755 IMGUI_API void AddCallback(ImDrawCallback callback, void* callback_data); // Your rendering function must check for 'UserCallback' in ImDrawCmd and call the function instead of rendering triangles.
2756 IMGUI_API void AddDrawCmd(); // This is useful if you need to forcefully create a new draw call (to allow for dependent rendering / blending). Otherwise primitives are merged into the same draw-call as much as possible
2757 IMGUI_API ImDrawList* CloneOutput() const; // Create a clone of the CmdBuffer/IdxBuffer/VtxBuffer.
2758
2759 // Advanced: Channels
2760 // - Use to split render into layers. By switching channels to can render out-of-order (e.g. submit FG primitives before BG primitives)
2761 // - Use to minimize draw calls (e.g. if going back-and-forth between multiple clipping rectangles, prefer to append into separate channels then merge at the end)
2762 // - This API shouldn't have been in ImDrawList in the first place!
2763 // Prefer using your own persistent instance of ImDrawListSplitter as you can stack them.
2764 // Using the ImDrawList::ChannelsXXXX you cannot stack a split over another.
2765 inline void ChannelsSplit(int count) { _Splitter.Split(this, count); }
2766 inline void ChannelsMerge() { _Splitter.Merge(this); }
2767 inline void ChannelsSetCurrent(int n) { _Splitter.SetCurrentChannel(this, n); }
2768
2769 // Advanced: Primitives allocations
2770 // - We render triangles (three vertices)
2771 // - All primitives needs to be reserved via PrimReserve() beforehand.
2772 IMGUI_API void PrimReserve(int idx_count, int vtx_count);
2773 IMGUI_API void PrimUnreserve(int idx_count, int vtx_count);
2774 IMGUI_API void PrimRect(const ImVec2& a, const ImVec2& b, ImU32 col); // Axis aligned rectangle (composed of two triangles)
2775 IMGUI_API void PrimRectUV(const ImVec2& a, const ImVec2& b, const ImVec2& uv_a, const ImVec2& uv_b, ImU32 col);
2776 IMGUI_API void PrimQuadUV(const ImVec2& a, const ImVec2& b, const ImVec2& c, const ImVec2& d, const ImVec2& uv_a, const ImVec2& uv_b, const ImVec2& uv_c, const ImVec2& uv_d, ImU32 col);
2777 inline void PrimWriteVtx(const ImVec2& pos, const ImVec2& uv, ImU32 col) { _VtxWritePtr->pos = pos; _VtxWritePtr->uv = uv; _VtxWritePtr->col = col; _VtxWritePtr++; _VtxCurrentIdx++; }
2778 inline void PrimWriteIdx(ImDrawIdx idx) { *_IdxWritePtr = idx; _IdxWritePtr++; }
2779 inline void PrimVtx(const ImVec2& pos, const ImVec2& uv, ImU32 col) { PrimWriteIdx((ImDrawIdx)_VtxCurrentIdx); PrimWriteVtx(pos, uv, col); } // Write vertex with unique index
2780
2781 // Obsolete names
2782 //inline void AddBezierCurve(const ImVec2& p1, const ImVec2& p2, const ImVec2& p3, const ImVec2& p4, ImU32 col, float thickness, int num_segments = 0) { AddBezierCubic(p1, p2, p3, p4, col, thickness, num_segments); } // OBSOLETED in 1.80 (Jan 2021)
2783 //inline void PathBezierCurveTo(const ImVec2& p2, const ImVec2& p3, const ImVec2& p4, int num_segments = 0) { PathBezierCubicCurveTo(p2, p3, p4, num_segments); } // OBSOLETED in 1.80 (Jan 2021)
2784
2785 // [Internal helpers]
2786 IMGUI_API void _ResetForNewFrame();
2787 IMGUI_API void _ClearFreeMemory();
2788 IMGUI_API void _PopUnusedDrawCmd();
2789 IMGUI_API void _TryMergeDrawCmds();
2790 IMGUI_API void _OnChangedClipRect();
2791 IMGUI_API void _OnChangedTextureID();
2792 IMGUI_API void _OnChangedVtxOffset();
2793 IMGUI_API int _CalcCircleAutoSegmentCount(float radius) const;
2794 IMGUI_API void _PathArcToFastEx(const ImVec2& center, float radius, int a_min_sample, int a_max_sample, int a_step);
2795 IMGUI_API void _PathArcToN(const ImVec2& center, float radius, float a_min, float a_max, int num_segments);
2796};

2798// All draw data to render a Dear ImGui frame
2799// (NB: the style and the naming convention here is a little inconsistent, we currently preserve them for backward compatibility purpose,
2800// as this is one of the oldest structure exposed by the library! Basically, ImDrawList == CmdList)
2801struct ImDrawData
2802{
2803 bool Valid; // Only valid after Render() is called and before the next NewFrame() is called.
2804 int CmdListsCount; // Number of ImDrawList* to render (should always be == CmdLists.size)
2805 int TotalIdxCount; // For convenience, sum of all ImDrawList's IdxBuffer.Size
2806 int TotalVtxCount; // For convenience, sum of all ImDrawList's VtxBuffer.Size
2807 ImVector<ImDrawList*> CmdLists; // Array of ImDrawList* to render. The ImDrawLists are owned by ImGuiContext and only pointed to from here.
2808 ImVec2 DisplayPos; // Top-left position of the viewport to render (== top-left of the orthogonal projection matrix to use) (== GetMainViewport()->Pos for the main viewport, == (0.0) in most single-viewport applications)
2809 ImVec2 DisplaySize; // Size of the viewport to render (== GetMainViewport()->Size for the main viewport, == io.DisplaySize in most single-viewport applications)
2810 ImVec2 FramebufferScale; // Amount of pixels for each unit of DisplaySize. Based on io.DisplayFramebufferScale. Generally (1,1) on normal display, (2,2) on OSX with Retina display.
2811 ImGuiViewport* OwnerViewport; // Viewport carrying the ImDrawData instance, might be of use to the renderer (generally not).
2812
2813 // Functions
2814 ImDrawData() { Clear(); }
2815 IMGUI_API void Clear();
2816 IMGUI_API void AddDrawList(ImDrawList* draw_list); // Helper to add an external draw list into an existing ImDrawData.
2817 IMGUI_API void DeIndexAllBuffers(); // Helper to convert all buffers from indexed to non-indexed, in case you cannot render indexed. Note: this is slow and most likely a waste of resources. Always prefer indexed rendering!
2818 IMGUI_API void ScaleClipRects(const ImVec2& fb_scale); // Helper to scale the ClipRect field of each ImDrawCmd. Use if your final output buffer is at a different scale than Dear ImGui expects, or if there is a difference between your window resolution and framebuffer resolution.
2819};

2821//-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
2822// [SECTION] Font API (ImFontConfig, ImFontGlyph, ImFontAtlasFlags, ImFontAtlas, ImFontGlyphRangesBuilder, ImFont)
2823//-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
2824
2825struct ImFontConfig
2826{
2827 void* FontData; // // TTF/OTF data
2828 int FontDataSize; // // TTF/OTF data size
2829 bool FontDataOwnedByAtlas; // true // TTF/OTF data ownership taken by the container ImFontAtlas (will delete memory itself).
2830 int FontNo; // 0 // Index of font within TTF/OTF file
2831 float SizePixels; // // Size in pixels for rasterizer (more or less maps to the resulting font height).
2832 int OversampleH; // 2 // Rasterize at higher quality for sub-pixel positioning. Note the difference between 2 and 3 is minimal. You can reduce this to 1 for large glyphs save memory. Read https://github.com/nothings/stb/blob/master/tests/oversample/README.md for details.
2833 int OversampleV; // 1 // Rasterize at higher quality for sub-pixel positioning. This is not really useful as we don't use sub-pixel positions on the Y axis.
2834 bool PixelSnapH; // false // Align every glyph to pixel boundary. Useful e.g. if you are merging a non-pixel aligned font with the default font. If enabled, you can set OversampleH/V to 1.
2835 ImVec2 GlyphExtraSpacing; // 0, 0 // Extra spacing (in pixels) between glyphs. Only X axis is supported for now.
2836 ImVec2 GlyphOffset; // 0, 0 // Offset all glyphs from this font input.
2837 const ImWchar* GlyphRanges; // NULL // THE ARRAY DATA NEEDS TO PERSIST AS LONG AS THE FONT IS ALIVE. Pointer to a user-provided list of Unicode range (2 value per range, values are inclusive, zero-terminated list).
2838 float GlyphMinAdvanceX; // 0 // Minimum AdvanceX for glyphs, set Min to align font icons, set both Min/Max to enforce mono-space font
2839 float GlyphMaxAdvanceX; // FLT_MAX // Maximum AdvanceX for glyphs
2840 bool MergeMode; // false // Merge into previous ImFont, so you can combine multiple inputs font into one ImFont (e.g. ASCII font + icons + Japanese glyphs). You may want to use GlyphOffset.y when merge font of different heights.
2841 unsigned int FontBuilderFlags; // 0 // Settings for custom font builder. THIS IS BUILDER IMPLEMENTATION DEPENDENT. Leave as zero if unsure.
2842 float RasterizerMultiply; // 1.0f // Linearly brighten (>1.0f) or darken (<1.0f) font output. Brightening small fonts may be a good workaround to make them more readable. This is a silly thing we may remove in the future.
2843 float RasterizerDensity; // 1.0f // DPI scale for rasterization, not altering other font metrics: make it easy to swap between e.g. a 100% and a 400% fonts for a zooming display. IMPORTANT: If you increase this it is expected that you increase font scale accordingly, otherwise quality may look lowered.
2844 ImWchar EllipsisChar; // -1 // Explicitly specify unicode codepoint of ellipsis character. When fonts are being merged first specified ellipsis will be used.
2845
2846 // [Internal]
2847 char Name[40]; // Name (strictly to ease debugging)
2848 ImFont* DstFont;
2849
2850 IMGUI_API ImFontConfig();
2851};
2852
2853// Hold rendering data for one glyph.
2854// (Note: some language parsers may fail to convert the 31+1 bitfield members, in this case maybe drop store a single u32 or we can rework this)
2855struct ImFontGlyph
2856{
2857 unsigned int Colored : 1; // Flag to indicate glyph is colored and should generally ignore tinting (make it usable with no shift on little-endian as this is used in loops)
2858 unsigned int Visible : 1; // Flag to indicate glyph has no visible pixels (e.g. space). Allow early out when rendering.
2859 unsigned int Codepoint : 30; // 0x0000..0x10FFFF
2860 float AdvanceX; // Distance to next character (= data from font + ImFontConfig::GlyphExtraSpacing.x baked in)
2861 float X0, Y0, X1, Y1; // Glyph corners
2862 float U0, V0, U1, V1; // Texture coordinates
2863};
2864
2865// Helper to build glyph ranges from text/string data. Feed your application strings/characters to it then call BuildRanges().
2866// This is essentially a tightly packed of vector of 64k booleans = 8KB storage.
2867struct ImFontGlyphRangesBuilder
2868{
2869 ImVector<ImU32> UsedChars; // Store 1-bit per Unicode code point (0=unused, 1=used)
2870
2871 ImFontGlyphRangesBuilder() { Clear(); }
2872 inline void Clear() { int size_in_bytes = (IM_UNICODE_CODEPOINT_MAX + 1) / 8; UsedChars.resize(size_in_bytes / (int)sizeof(ImU32)); memset(UsedChars.Data, 0, (size_t)size_in_bytes); }
2873 inline bool GetBit(size_t n) const { int off = (int)(n >> 5); ImU32 mask = 1u << (n & 31); return (UsedChars[off] & mask) != 0; } // Get bit n in the array
2874 inline void SetBit(size_t n) { int off = (int)(n >> 5); ImU32 mask = 1u << (n & 31); UsedChars[off] |= mask; } // Set bit n in the array
2875 inline void AddChar(ImWchar c) { SetBit(c); } // Add character
2876 IMGUI_API void AddText(const char* text, const char* text_end = NULL); // Add string (each character of the UTF-8 string are added)
2877 IMGUI_API void AddRanges(const ImWchar* ranges); // Add ranges, e.g. builder.AddRanges(ImFontAtlas::GetGlyphRangesDefault()) to force add all of ASCII/Latin+Ext
2878 IMGUI_API void BuildRanges(ImVector<ImWchar>* out_ranges); // Output new ranges
2879};
2880
2881// See ImFontAtlas::AddCustomRectXXX functions.
2882struct ImFontAtlasCustomRect
2883{
2884 unsigned short Width, Height; // Input // Desired rectangle dimension
2885 unsigned short X, Y; // Output // Packed position in Atlas
2886 unsigned int GlyphID; // Input // For custom font glyphs only (ID < 0x110000)
2887 float GlyphAdvanceX; // Input // For custom font glyphs only: glyph xadvance
2888 ImVec2 GlyphOffset; // Input // For custom font glyphs only: glyph display offset
2889 ImFont* Font; // Input // For custom font glyphs only: target font
2890 ImFontAtlasCustomRect() { Width = Height = 0; X = Y = 0xFFFF; GlyphID = 0; GlyphAdvanceX = 0.0f; GlyphOffset = ImVec2(0, 0); Font = NULL; }
2891 bool IsPacked() const { return X != 0xFFFF; }
2892};
2893
2894// Flags for ImFontAtlas build
2895enum ImFontAtlasFlags_
2896{
2897 ImFontAtlasFlags_None = 0,
2898 ImFontAtlasFlags_NoPowerOfTwoHeight = 1 << 0, // Don't round the height to next power of two
2899 ImFontAtlasFlags_NoMouseCursors = 1 << 1, // Don't build software mouse cursors into the atlas (save a little texture memory)
2900 ImFontAtlasFlags_NoBakedLines = 1 << 2, // Don't build thick line textures into the atlas (save a little texture memory, allow support for point/nearest filtering). The AntiAliasedLinesUseTex features uses them, otherwise they will be rendered using polygons (more expensive for CPU/GPU).
2901};
2902
2903// Load and rasterize multiple TTF/OTF fonts into a same texture. The font atlas will build a single texture holding:
2904// - One or more fonts.
2905// - Custom graphics data needed to render the shapes needed by Dear ImGui.
2906// - Mouse cursor shapes for software cursor rendering (unless setting 'Flags |= ImFontAtlasFlags_NoMouseCursors' in the font atlas).
2907// It is the user-code responsibility to setup/build the atlas, then upload the pixel data into a texture accessible by your graphics api.
2908// - Optionally, call any of the AddFont*** functions. If you don't call any, the default font embedded in the code will be loaded for you.
2909// - Call GetTexDataAsAlpha8() or GetTexDataAsRGBA32() to build and retrieve pixels data.
2910// - Upload the pixels data into a texture within your graphics system (see imgui_impl_xxxx.cpp examples)
2911// - Call SetTexID(my_tex_id); and pass the pointer/identifier to your texture in a format natural to your graphics API.
2912// This value will be passed back to you during rendering to identify the texture. Read FAQ entry about ImTextureID for more details.
2913// Common pitfalls:
2914// - If you pass a 'glyph_ranges' array to AddFont*** functions, you need to make sure that your array persist up until the
2915// atlas is build (when calling GetTexData*** or Build()). We only copy the pointer, not the data.
2916// - Important: By default, AddFontFromMemoryTTF() takes ownership of the data. Even though we are not writing to it, we will free the pointer on destruction.
2917// You can set font_cfg->FontDataOwnedByAtlas=false to keep ownership of your data and it won't be freed,
2918// - Even though many functions are suffixed with "TTF", OTF data is supported just as well.
2919// - This is an old API and it is currently awkward for those and various other reasons! We will address them in the future!
2920struct ImFontAtlas
2921{
2922 IMGUI_API ImFontAtlas();
2923 IMGUI_API ~ImFontAtlas();
2924 IMGUI_API ImFont* AddFont(const ImFontConfig* font_cfg);
2925 IMGUI_API ImFont* AddFontDefault(const ImFontConfig* font_cfg = NULL);
2926 IMGUI_API ImFont* AddFontFromFileTTF(ImGuiContext* ctx, const char* filename, float size_pixels, const ImFontConfig* font_cfg = NULL, const ImWchar* glyph_ranges = NULL);
2927 IMGUI_API ImFont* AddFontFromMemoryTTF(void* font_data, int font_data_size, float size_pixels, const ImFontConfig* font_cfg = NULL, const ImWchar* glyph_ranges = NULL); // Note: Transfer ownership of 'ttf_data' to ImFontAtlas! Will be deleted after destruction of the atlas. Set font_cfg->FontDataOwnedByAtlas=false to keep ownership of your data and it won't be freed.
2928 IMGUI_API ImFont* AddFontFromMemoryCompressedTTF(const void* compressed_font_data, int compressed_font_data_size, float size_pixels, const ImFontConfig* font_cfg = NULL, const ImWchar* glyph_ranges = NULL); // 'compressed_font_data' still owned by caller. Compress with binary_to_compressed_c.cpp.
2929 IMGUI_API ImFont* AddFontFromMemoryCompressedBase85TTF(const char* compressed_font_data_base85, float size_pixels, const ImFontConfig* font_cfg = NULL, const ImWchar* glyph_ranges = NULL); // 'compressed_font_data_base85' still owned by caller. Compress with binary_to_compressed_c.cpp with -base85 parameter.
2930 IMGUI_API void ClearInputData(); // Clear input data (all ImFontConfig structures including sizes, TTF data, glyph ranges, etc.) = all the data used to build the texture and fonts.
2931 IMGUI_API void ClearTexData(); // Clear output texture data (CPU side). Saves RAM once the texture has been copied to graphics memory.
2932 IMGUI_API void ClearFonts(); // Clear output font data (glyphs storage, UV coordinates).
2933 IMGUI_API void Clear(); // Clear all input and output.
2934
2935 // Build atlas, retrieve pixel data.
2936 // User is in charge of copying the pixels into graphics memory (e.g. create a texture with your engine). Then store your texture handle with SetTexID().
2937 // The pitch is always = Width * BytesPerPixels (1 or 4)
2938 // Building in RGBA32 format is provided for convenience and compatibility, but note that unless you manually manipulate or copy color data into
2939 // the texture (e.g. when using the AddCustomRect*** api), then the RGB pixels emitted will always be white (~75% of memory/bandwidth waste.
2940 IMGUI_API bool Build(); // Build pixels data. This is called automatically for you by the GetTexData*** functions.
2941 IMGUI_API void GetTexDataAsAlpha8(unsigned char** out_pixels, int* out_width, int* out_height, int* out_bytes_per_pixel = NULL); // 1 byte per-pixel
2942 IMGUI_API void GetTexDataAsRGBA32(unsigned char** out_pixels, int* out_width, int* out_height, int* out_bytes_per_pixel = NULL); // 4 bytes-per-pixel
2943 bool IsBuilt() const { return Fonts.Size > 0 && TexReady; } // Bit ambiguous: used to detect when user didn't build texture but effectively we should check TexID != 0 except that would be backend dependent...
2944 void SetTexID(ImTextureID id) { TexID = id; }
2945
2946 //-------------------------------------------
2947 // Glyph Ranges
2948 //-------------------------------------------
2949
2950 // Helpers to retrieve list of common Unicode ranges (2 value per range, values are inclusive, zero-terminated list)
2951 // NB: Make sure that your string are UTF-8 and NOT in your local code page.
2952 // Read https://github.com/ocornut/imgui/blob/master/docs/FONTS.md/#about-utf-8-encoding for details.
2953 // NB: Consider using ImFontGlyphRangesBuilder to build glyph ranges from textual data.
2954 IMGUI_API const ImWchar* GetGlyphRangesDefault(); // Basic Latin, Extended Latin
2955 IMGUI_API const ImWchar* GetGlyphRangesGreek(); // Default + Greek and Coptic
2956 IMGUI_API const ImWchar* GetGlyphRangesKorean(); // Default + Korean characters
2957 IMGUI_API const ImWchar* GetGlyphRangesJapanese(); // Default + Hiragana, Katakana, Half-Width, Selection of 2999 Ideographs
2958 IMGUI_API const ImWchar* GetGlyphRangesChineseFull(); // Default + Half-Width + Japanese Hiragana/Katakana + full set of about 21000 CJK Unified Ideographs
2959 IMGUI_API const ImWchar* GetGlyphRangesChineseSimplifiedCommon();// Default + Half-Width + Japanese Hiragana/Katakana + set of 2500 CJK Unified Ideographs for common simplified Chinese
2960 IMGUI_API const ImWchar* GetGlyphRangesCyrillic(); // Default + about 400 Cyrillic characters
2961 IMGUI_API const ImWchar* GetGlyphRangesThai(); // Default + Thai characters
2962 IMGUI_API const ImWchar* GetGlyphRangesVietnamese(); // Default + Vietnamese characters
2963
2964 //-------------------------------------------
2965 // [BETA] Custom Rectangles/Glyphs API
2966 //-------------------------------------------
2967
2968 // You can request arbitrary rectangles to be packed into the atlas, for your own purposes.
2969 // - After calling Build(), you can query the rectangle position and render your pixels.
2970 // - If you render colored output, set 'atlas->TexPixelsUseColors = true' as this may help some backends decide of prefered texture format.
2971 // - You can also request your rectangles to be mapped as font glyph (given a font + Unicode point),
2972 // so you can render e.g. custom colorful icons and use them as regular glyphs.
2973 // - Read docs/FONTS.md for more details about using colorful icons.
2974 // - Note: this API may be redesigned later in order to support multi-monitor varying DPI settings.
2975 IMGUI_API int AddCustomRectRegular(int width, int height);
2976 IMGUI_API int AddCustomRectFontGlyph(ImFont* font, ImWchar id, int width, int height, float advance_x, const ImVec2& offset = ImVec2(0, 0));
2977 ImFontAtlasCustomRect* GetCustomRectByIndex(int index) { IM_ASSERT(index >= 0); return &CustomRects[index]; }
2978
2979 // [Internal]
2980 IMGUI_API void CalcCustomRectUV(const ImFontAtlasCustomRect* rect, ImVec2* out_uv_min, ImVec2* out_uv_max) const;
2981 IMGUI_API bool GetMouseCursorTexData(ImGuiMouseCursor cursor, ImVec2* out_offset, ImVec2* out_size, ImVec2 out_uv_border[2], ImVec2 out_uv_fill[2]);
2982
2983 //-------------------------------------------
2984 // Members
2985 //-------------------------------------------
2986
2987 ImFontAtlasFlags Flags; // Build flags (see ImFontAtlasFlags_)
2988 ImTextureID TexID; // User data to refer to the texture once it has been uploaded to user's graphic systems. It is passed back to you during rendering via the ImDrawCmd structure.
2989 int TexDesiredWidth; // Texture width desired by user before Build(). Must be a power-of-two. If have many glyphs your graphics API have texture size restrictions you may want to increase texture width to decrease height.
2990 int TexGlyphPadding; // Padding between glyphs within texture in pixels. Defaults to 1. If your rendering method doesn't rely on bilinear filtering you may set this to 0 (will also need to set AntiAliasedLinesUseTex = false).
2991 bool Locked; // Marked as Locked by ImGui::NewFrame() so attempt to modify the atlas will assert.
2992 void* UserData; // Store your own atlas related user-data (if e.g. you have multiple font atlas).
2993
2994 // [Internal]
2995 // NB: Access texture data via GetTexData*() calls! Which will setup a default font for you.
2996 bool TexReady; // Set when texture was built matching current font input
2997 bool TexPixelsUseColors; // Tell whether our texture data is known to use colors (rather than just alpha channel), in order to help backend select a format.
2998 unsigned char* TexPixelsAlpha8; // 1 component per pixel, each component is unsigned 8-bit. Total size = TexWidth * TexHeight
2999 unsigned int* TexPixelsRGBA32; // 4 component per pixel, each component is unsigned 8-bit. Total size = TexWidth * TexHeight * 4
3000 int TexWidth; // Texture width calculated during Build().
3001 int TexHeight; // Texture height calculated during Build().
3002 ImVec2 TexUvScale; // = (1.0f/TexWidth, 1.0f/TexHeight)
3003 ImVec2 TexUvWhitePixel; // Texture coordinates to a white pixel
3004 ImVector<ImFont*> Fonts; // Hold all the fonts returned by AddFont*. Fonts[0] is the default font upon calling ImGui::NewFrame(), use ImGui::PushFont()/PopFont() to change the current font.
3005 ImVector<ImFontAtlasCustomRect> CustomRects; // Rectangles for packing custom texture data into the atlas.
3006 ImVector<ImFontConfig> ConfigData; // Configuration data
3007 ImVec4 TexUvLines[IM_DRAWLIST_TEX_LINES_WIDTH_MAX + 1]; // UVs for baked anti-aliased lines
3008
3009 // [Internal] Font builder
3010 const ImFontBuilderIO* FontBuilderIO; // Opaque interface to a font builder (default to stb_truetype, can be changed to use FreeType by defining IMGUI_ENABLE_FREETYPE).
3011 unsigned int FontBuilderFlags; // Shared flags (for all fonts) for custom font builder. THIS IS BUILD IMPLEMENTATION DEPENDENT. Per-font override is also available in ImFontConfig.
3012
3013 // [Internal] Packing data
3014 int PackIdMouseCursors; // Custom texture rectangle ID for white pixel and mouse cursors
3015 int PackIdLines; // Custom texture rectangle ID for baked anti-aliased lines
3016
3017 // [Obsolete]
3018 //typedef ImFontAtlasCustomRect CustomRect; // OBSOLETED in 1.72+
3019 //typedef ImFontGlyphRangesBuilder GlyphRangesBuilder; // OBSOLETED in 1.67+
3020};
